<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish Report Suspects Russia, NATO of Submarine Intrusions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian and NATO submarines
may have deliberately violated the Swedish waters in recent years,
said the local press quoting a government report.
</P>
<P>
The allegations of Russian and NATO intrusion were made by the
foreign ministry of Sweden, a country considering itself as
neutral in foreign policies, in a classified report.
</P>
<P>
The report, as cited by the press that has acquired access to
parts of its findings, says Russia is the country which has the
most numerous, the most far-reaching and the most important
reasons for submarine intrusions.
</P>
<P>
NATO submarines may have reasons to make intrusions too, it
says, but most evidences speak against individual NATO countries
carrying on systematic underwater activities.
</P>
<P>
However, the report notes that the motives and reasons are no
evidence of intrusions.
</P>
<P>
The report was based on an investigation by a special group
authorized to scrutinize submarine intrusions during the period
between 1989 and 1995 from a security policy aspect.
</P>
<P>
According to Swedish Foreign Minister Lena Hjelm-Wallen, the
motives described by the document are not enough to identify a
country as an intruder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
