<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Rights Talks in APEC Summit Agenda, Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- There will be no discussion of
human rights and democracy when Canada hosts a summit of 18
leaders of Asia Pacific region in Vancouver this Autumn.
</P>
<P>
Discussion of rights issues "is certainly not going to happen,"
said John Klassen, director-general for the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation forum (APEC) in Canada's Department of Foreign
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Canadian government has also declined to endorse a
parallel Vancouver conference on trade and rights, according to
today's Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
In Canada's approach to APEC, tariff reductions and bolstered
economies come first, the paper noted.
</P>
<P>
Political and human rights in APEC countries and regions is "a
very sensitive issue," Klassen was quoted as saying. "You're not
going to slip it by anyone (onto an APEC agenda)."
</P>
<P>
Taking an aggressive stand would get nowhere under APEC's veto
system and would undermine Canada's quiet diplomacy, he added.
</P>
<P>
Some Canadian diplomats conceded that Vancouver is not the
right place for rights talks.
</P>
<P>
The summit of 18 economies, which account for half of the
world's economic production and two-thirds of the population, has
its own rules, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The week-long Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation forum
culminates with a meeting on November 24-25 of leaders of 18
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to draw 5,000 delegates and worldwide attention
from 3,000 journalists, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
