<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Dramatically Raise Fuel Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria's caretaker government
announced today to raise fuel retail prices by up to 200 percent
as of Tuesday, adding that more price hikes could be coming.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came when many gas stations went without any
petroleum supply and people had to wait in line for about eight
hours to buy their ration of 20 liters in the past weeks.
</P>
<P>
Price for the most ordinary petroleum will rise to 910 lev
(about 0.31 U.S. dollars) from 328 lev (0.11 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The caretaker government headed by Prime Minister Stefan
Sofiianski has ordered a ban on fuel exports before April 30.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent poll, only 13 percent of those surveyed
said they would continue to drive their own automobiles and 20
percent said they would only use their family cars in case of
emergency.
</P>
<P>
The severe fuel shortage has forced some cities to stop public
transport services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
