<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Bank Pressing Ukraine for Further Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) is planning to double its
loans to Ukraine in 1997 if the country continues economic reforms
and improves the investment climate.
</P>
<P>
This year, the EBRD may provide Ukraine with an additional
300-600 million U.S. dollars, which will equal or exceed its total
loans to this former Soviet republic in the past four years, said
Jaroslav Kinach, the EBRD's representative here.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the EBRD, a multilateral official aid institute
with a mission to finance private enterprises in Eastern Europe,
has extended loans worth 440 million dollars to Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
However, Kinach said, increased financial support depends
largely on the Ukrainian government's will and ability to improve
investment conditions in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
"Ukraine is a priority country, but our success in financing
project depends on Ukraine's ability to implement reforms. If
Ukraine is successful, we can be successful," he said.
</P>
<P>
The EBRD official applauded Ukraine's achievements in reining
in inflation and reforming its currency since its independence in
1991 but said the government "has not done enough to make life
easier for businessmen and investors, both foreign and local."
</P>
<P>
"As difficult as it is, we need to push the government when
they stray off the course of reforms or hesitate too much," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The government has submitted a package of economic and social
reforms, which are partly designed to improve the business
climate, to the Ukrainian parliament for approval.
</P>
<P>
If the package is not approved by the parliament, Kinach said,
the consequences will spur a sharp decline in foreign investment
and inflation and currency devaluation will follow.
</P>
<P>
"The alternatives are truly terrible to contemplate," the EBRD
official warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
