<HEADLINE> Lesotho's Rebel Police Leader Disappears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's rebel police
leader Phakiso Molise who surrendered Sunday after a military
crackdown on an 11-day police mutiny has disappeared from his
hideout in the Maseru Palace of King Letsie III.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Parliament early today, Lesotho's Deputy Prime
Minister Pakalitha Mosisili said King Letsie III has informed Prime
Minister Ntsu Mokhehle that Molise and a fellow policeman had
escaped from his Maseru Palace.
</P>
<P>
Molise and seven junior police officers, along with 400
mutinying policemen, seized control of the Police Headquarters on
February 6, causing a disruption in police service throughout the
land-locked southern African country.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the Lesotho Defence Force (LDF) quelled the police
mutiny with artillery shells and machine-gun fire, bringing the
police crisis to an end.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the prime minister, Deputy Prime
Minister Mosisili said the government was surprised when being
told that Molise and some of the rebels were staying in the
King's Palace as the LDF attacked on Police Headquarters and the
Maseru Central Charge Office.
</P>
<P>
All the rebel policemen except Molise at the King's palace
were handed over to the army after the attack, but Molise
requested the King for an assurance that he would not be killed
by the army, said Mosisili.
</P>
<P>
Following further discussions with the prime minister, the
King promised unreservedly that Molise would be handed over to
the army.
</P>
<P>
However, Mosisili told Parliament that up to last night the King
refused to hand over Molise. enditem

=02171634

=02171640
