<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Secretary of State to Visit EU Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The relations between the
European Union and the United States will top the agenda on
Tuesday's talks between U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and European Commission President Jacques Santer.
</P>
<P>
During her visit to the EU's executive, Albright will discuss
with Santer how to "further substantiate" the New Transatlantic
Agenda, signed in Madrid a year ago and designed to improve EU-US
cooperation in a wide range of areas, a Commission spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year, EU-US relations have been strained, mainly
because of the U.S. Helms-Burton Act.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. law enacted last March allows naturalized U.S.
citizens to sue foreign firms or individuals trading with
Cuba. U.S. President Bill Clinton has twice suspended that
provision for six months -- the last time on January 3.
</P>
<P>
The EU insisted that it wants to normalize relations with the
United States. But it refused to consider easing their opposition
to the Helms-Burton Act.
</P>
<P>
"Our stand remains the same as we already announced," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
EU trade commissioner Leon Brittan said in Geneva on Saturday
that the EU was actively negotiating a resolution of the dispute
with the United States, and had deferred the date for the
nomination of a disputes panel until February 20.
</P>
<P>
But he cautioned that in the absence of a better offer than
that had so far been made by Washington, a panel would be named by
the World Trade Organization's Director-General Renato Ruggiero on
February 20.
</P>
<P>
EU and U.S. officials will also discuss the EU's Economic and
Monetary Union (EMU) and its impact on the international monetary
market. In addition, the meeting will focus on the enlargement
process of the European Union, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
This is Albright's first overseas trip since taking office in
January. Brussels is the forth leg of Albright's tour which also
brings her to Paris, Rome, Bonn, London, Moscow, Seoul, Tokyo and
Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
