<HEADLINE> Urgent: India Deeply Regrets U.S. Move to Expel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 17 (Xinhua) -- India today said it "deeply
regretted" the U.S. State Department's decision to expel two
Indian diplomats who were discharging their normal
responsibilities as consular officers and categorically rejected
any implication to the contrary, Press Trust of India reported.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, the U.S. State Department
confirmed Saturday that the U.S. was requesting the Indian
government to withdraw the two officials for activities
incompatible with their consular status.
</P>
<P>
An Indian External Affairs Ministry spokesman said it appears
from media reports that the action has been taken in retaliation
to New Delhi's decision to send back two American diplomats over
the Ratan Sehgal espionage affair.
</P>
<P>
Sehgal was a senior Indian anti-espionage official who
allegedly maintained unauthorized contacts with the two American
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the two Indian officials would be returning
to India shortly.
</P>
<P>
"Viewing this unnecessary incident, in the broader perspective
of mature Indo-U.S. relations, India will continue to work with
the United States in improving and expanding friendly ties and
cooperation," the spokesman said in a statement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
