<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E-Mail Used as Conduit of Racial Prejudice on US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The use of E-mail to send
hate messages is a growing concern on many college campuses in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The first sign of such things happened on January 31 of last
year when Joon Park, a junior at Indiana University in Bloomington
received a phone call from a frantic student that a hate message
has been sent via electronic mail to 700 members of the Asian
Students Association, the group of which Park is the president.
</P>
<P>
The obscenity-laden message included racial epithets and
ordered the students to leave the United States. Less than a week
later, a similar message was sent to the asssociation's office.
</P>
<P>
"There's a lot of resentment toward Asians on this campus, and
these messages are a way to express feelings to a large number of
people and easily cover your tracks," Park was quoted on Sunday by
the New York Times as saying.
</P>
<P>
Although it is difficult to know how prevalent such messages
are, they seem to be increasing, said the American Council on
Education, which is based in Washington and represents 1,700
colleges.
</P>
<P>
At the University of California where Asian-American Population
is about 50 percent, according to a report of the New York Times,
the Federal Government has for the first time prosecuted a hate
crime committed by a former student, Richard Machado, who is
accused of threatening 58 students last fall, most of them
Asian-Americans. He warned Asian-American students that if they did
not leave the campus,"I personally will make it my life career to
find and kill everyone of you personally."
</P>
<P>
E-mail harassment on campus has been examined, and the early
findings show that E-mail has become the most popular
communication tool on campus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
