<HEADLINE> Three S. African Airlines Form Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 17 (Xinhua) -- A memorandum of
understanding was signed here today between South African
Airways, SA Express Airways and SA Airlink, thus making them a
leading aviation network in Africa, the South African Press
Association (SAPA) has reproted.
</P>
<P>
The formation of this alliance would put its participants in a
position to operate the largest and the most modern fleet of
aircraft and to offer an extensive regional feeder network, SAPA
quoted a statement by the alliance as saying.
</P>
<P>
The primary objective of the allince was to provide an
integrated national aviation system which would service all routes
ranging from entry level to the national hubs and would offer
national over-border air transportation, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said the timing and planning of flight schedules
of the three airlines would be adjusted to offer a fully-integrated
service.
</P>
<P>
Although the three airlines would continue to operate
independently, there would be commonality in their branding in terms
of common check-in procedures and the general appearance of the
airlines, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
South African Airways, the main carrier in the alliance, would
continue to serve intercontinental traffic and the high passenger
volume route between the major cities in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, SA Express Airways and SA Airlink would concentrate on
providing more frequent flights on the various routes most suited to
small passenger planes, the statement said. enditem

