<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Aircraft Market in Next Decade Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEATTLE, February 17 (Xinhua) -- More than 5,800 commercial
jetliners will be built in the next decade, according to a
forecast made by an independent American firm.
</P>
<P>
These jetliners are valued at 367.2 billion U.S. dollars, or 56
percent of the total value of world aircraft production in the
1997-2006 period, said Teal Group, a Virginia-based defense and
aerospace market analysis firm.
</P>
<P>
According to the Teal report relased here today at the ongoing
annual meeting of the American Association for the Advancement of
Science, a total of 25,537 aircraft of all types valued at 655.5
billion U.S. dollars are expected to be built during the decade.
</P>
<P>
Next come fighters in terms of value: 2,846 valued at 110
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other types include helicopters, business aircraft, military
transports, regional aircraft and trainers.
</P>
<P>
Teal predicted that more than half of the commercial and
military airplanes will be built in the United States, although
the U.S. share of the aviation market will go down from 65.7
percent this year to 59 percent in 2006.
</P>
<P>
Europe will follow with a share of one third of the coming
world market, and its percentage will rise to 35.7 percent in 2006
from 29.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Analyzing the reason for the drop of U.S. share, Teal said that
ex-Soviet militaries and airlines will again be semi-viable
markets by 2006. Moreover, Britain, France and Germany have
next-generation defense systems not in production today but that
will be in 2006.
</P>
<P>
The "rest of the world" percentage of aircraft manufacturing
will slightly rise from 4.5 percent in 1996 to 5.4 percent a
decade later, Teal analysts said.
</P>
<P>
As far as builders are concerned, Boeing's leading share is
growing, thanks to the company's acquisition of McDonnell Douglas,
Teal said, expecting the percentage of its revenues form world
aircraft production to increase from 38.9 percent in 1997 to 44.2
percent in 2006.
</P>
<P>
However, the analysts said that the future world aircraft
market, to some extent, depends heavily on the decisions by giant
companies such as Boeing and Airbus.  
</P>
</TEXT>
