<HEADLINE> Famine Hits Somalia Due to Prolonged Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Severe drought and
political instability are causing a high death toll in war-torn
Somalia and forcing more and more people to pour into capital
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Following the closure of all kitchens where about 150,000
people were fed once a day in more than 30 camps and mosques
during the holy month of Ramadan, now Mogadishu is teeming with
street beggars.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-nine respected clan elders from Bay, Hiran,
Galgudud and Mudug signed a letter Sunday to call for
drought-famine relief, saying a dozen of people die of
famine-related diseases every day in these regions.
</P>
<P>
Residents living in river land now are reportedly eating the
peels of bananas and grapefruits due to the food crisis caused by
long drought.
</P>
<P>
Somalia is in a state of real drought, claimed the Moslem
Aid-UK agency which has recently completed a survey on drought
situation in Hiran, Bay, Lower Shabelle and Mogadishu
regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
Khalid Shufia Abdalla, the agency's representative, said that
with the help of the UN aid agency, UNICEF, the agency is opening
feeding camps in Wadajir Village 30 kilometers south of Mogadishu
and Hamar Weyne, Gubta, Animal Market and Medina
Enclave areas in the capital.
</P>
<P>
A French aid agency called ACF also runs some feeding centers
for children in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
