<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Finance Ministers View Belgian Convergence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 17 (Xinhua) -- EU finance ministers, holding
their monthly Council Meeting in Brussels today, welcomed
Belgium's strategy for fiscal consolidation after appraising the
country's new convergence program.
</P>
<P>
Covering the 1997-2000 period, the Belgian program has been
described by the ministers as general positive, even though a
further reduction in the debt ratio would be welcome.
</P>
<P>
Belgium has a fair sized safety margin to meet the three
percent public deficit relative to GDP(Gross Domestic Product)
criteria by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The cyclical macro-economic scenario decided up by the Belgian
authorities contemplate eroding the size of the deficit from 3.4
percent in 1996 to 2.9 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Over the next three years, the deficit should be respectively
two percent, 1.6 percent and 1.6 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Described by the ministers as ambitious yet credible, the
Belgium program has its merits, as is illustrated in the reversal
of the spiraling debt, which is set to fall from 130.4 percent of
GDP in 1996 to 127 percent in 1997 and eventually to settle at
120.5 percent of GDP by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers agreed to invite the Belgian authorities
and the European Commission(EC) to monitor the implementation of
the program and to report to the Council once a year.
</P>
<P>
According to the EC, updated program from France and Germany
are due to be studied on March 17.
</P>
<P>
Programs from Italy, Portugal, Denmark and the Netherlands
will get the same treatment on May 12.  
</P>
</TEXT>
