<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Denies Promise to US on Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu denied today that he had promised to the
United States not to build settlements in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after holding talks with visiting Mexican Foreign
Minister Jose Angel Gurria Trevino, Netanyahu, who just returned
from his U.S. visit earlier today, ridiculed press reports about
his promise.
</P>
<P>
"I'm simply amazed at what I am hearing here. Apparently,
somebody is trying to make headlines over nothing," Netanyahu
said, adding he would convene two meetings of the Ministerial
Committee on Jerusalem Affairs to discuss building settlements in
Har Homa neighborhood in east Jerusalem and "make all the
necessary decisions."
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister's Office announced later that the
ministerial committee would meet Tuesday to discuss specifically
road construction in Jerusalem, and a second meeting would be
held next week.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's media adviser David Bar-Illan also dismissed that
Netanyahu had made any promise to the U.S.. He reiterated the
government's stand that Jerusalem would be an indivisible
capital city of Israel, and the Jewish state would "build
whenever we feel like it and wherever we feel like it."
</P>
<P>
Bar-Illan admitted that the government was considering the
timing of settlement building in east Jerusalem for fear that it
would spark violent reaction from the Palestinians similar to
the last September bloodshed, due to the opening of a tunnel near
the holy site of the Al-Aqsa Mosque in the city, which killed
over 70 people.
</P>
<P>
But he vowed Israel would not live under threats of violence,
warning that if the Palestinians resorted to violence, the peace
process could be ruined.
</P>
<P>
"We have made very clear that the peace process cannot
continue with consistent threats of violence. Violence cannot be
made an option for the Palestinians, and if they accept violence
as an option, there will be no peace process," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some coalition and opposition lawmakers continued
to put pressure on Netanyahu to start immediately the building
plan in Har Homa neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
A group of coalition lawmakers from the Likud, Third Way and
National Religious Party have already declared that they would
topple the government if it did not go ahead with the building
plan.
</P>
<P>
Likud lawmaker Michael Kleiner, who heads the group, said it
now includes 28 Knesset (Parliament) members. He said the group
would demand Netanyahu keep his promises and commitments on the
Jerusalem issue.
</P>
<P>
Third Way's Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani said
today that it was the time to start the building. "It's time to
see more Israeli people in east Jerusalem and one of the ways is
to build settlements," he said, adding that the plan would
start very soon.
</P>
<P>
Likud's Communications Minister Limor Livnat said she believed
that Netanyahu would soon give the green-light for the building
project. She added that despite of the pressures from the
U.S. and the Palestinian side, the government would not
compromise on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Labor party, which was split over the issue,
decided today not to present a non-confidence motion over the
government's failure to go ahead with the building project.
</P>
<P>
Ehud Barak, former foreign minister and leading contender for
Labor's leadership, said he supported the plan of building in
east Jerusalem. But Yossi Beilin, another contender for Labor
leadership, argued that the timing was not good now to go ahead
with the building plan.
</P>
<P>
Beilin said while he supported the building project, which
was also promised by the previous Labor government, he thought
the best timing for it would be after the permanent talks with
the Palestinian side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
