<HEADLINE> Iran, Kazakhstan to Expand Bilateral Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Kazakhstan today
signed an agreement to enhance their cooperation in trade,
sciences and culture.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that the letter of
understanding was concluded at the end of the third session of
Tehran-Almaty joint economic commission which was held here
today.
</P>
<P>
Yuri Lavrinenko, Kazakh Minister of Transport and
Communications, said that a large part of the difficulties in
the way of expanding bilateral cooperation have been removed.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the volume of trade exchange between
the two countries would rise from the current year's 65 million
U.S. dollars to 100 million dollars in the future.
</P>
<P>
He said the fourth session of Tehran-Almaty joint economic
commission would be held in Kazakhstan next year.
</P>
<P>
According to the letter of understanding, Iran will set up a
branch of one of Iranian banks in Almaty after working out the
formalities in this respect and the National Bank of Kazakhstan
will help grant license for the operation of the Iranian bank
there.
</P>
<P>
The two countries reached the agreement to develop
telecommunications cooperation through optic fiber installation
and forming a joint company to carry out telecommunications
projects in Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Energy Ministry has voiced readiness to offer
technological know-how to Kazakhstan in the field of equipment
for electricity transmission and dam building, according to the
IRNA.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to facilitate the cooperation of
Iranian and Kazakh companies in the field of agriculture and
fishery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
