<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Finance Ministers Agree Aid for Armenia, Georgia, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Up to ECU 265 million(about
307 million U.S. dollars) will be on its way to Armenia, Georgia,
and if appropriate, to Tajikistan, in the form of ECU 170 million
in long-term loans and ECU 95 million in grants, according to a
decision made by EU finance ministers here today.
</P>
<P>
The ministers said in a statement after their monthly meeting
that they agreed in principle to provide exceptional financial
assistance to Armenia, Georgia, and that "a similar operation will
be considered for Tajikistan once circumstance allow".
</P>
<P>
This assistance, as what the ministers termed an "exceptional"
measure, was aimed to support the tough reform programs - and
the associated social costs - that Armenia, Georgia and Tajikistan
are undertaking.
</P>
<P>
On February 4, the European Commission has proposed to grant
ECU 50 million to these three countries in five equal annual
installments of ECU 10 million, from 1997 onwards.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, the finance ministers decided to invite the
Commission to augment the proposal for the loan, repayable over up
to 15 years, with higher grant elements, i.e. ECU 10 million in
1997 and ECU 17 million in each of the following five years.
</P>
<P>
But the ministers stressed that these grants should be used
only for early repayment of the loan of ECU 170 million mentioned
above.
</P>
<P>
The Commission will negotiate conditions for the assistance, and
Tajikistan will qualify only if it wins the support of the
International Monetary Fund this April.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
