<HEADLINE> Monza F1 Track Keeps Right to Hold Italian GP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Monza Formula One racetrack
officials shook off opposition from environmentalists to win the
right to hold Italy's Grand Prix race here for another ten years,
according to reports reaching here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Monza city council extended a contract to hold the Formula
One race on the track inside the city's huge park until 2007, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Disputes between environmentalists and track officials over
cutting down trees to extend the racetrack's safety zone
jeopardized the race in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Under the new contract, race track officials will pay the city
of Monza rent of 470,000 dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted track officials as saying that they will now
seek a ten-year renewal of their contract with Formula One's
governing body to continue hosting the Italian Grand Prix in
Monza. 
</P>
