<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Anticipates Role in Reviving Syrian-Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Dutch Foreign Minister Hans Van
Mierlo said today that the European Union (EU) may play an
affirmative role in restarting the Israel-Syrian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Mierlo, whose country currently holds the rotating EU
presidency, made remark here after talks with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak and Foreign Minister Amr Moussa on the Mideast peace
process this morning.
</P>
<P>
The EU is trying to do its best for the resumption of the
process on the Syrian-Israeli track, the envoy said, adding that
he had visited Syria and met with its president at the request of
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
"It would not be impossible, during the coming months, for
Europe to play an affirmative role to secure the resumption of the
process on this track," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian talks have frozen since last March after a
series of suicide bombings in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Syria wants Israel to return the Golan Heights captured in the
1967 Mideast war for a comprehensive peace agreement. But Israel
only agrees to a partial withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference with his Dutch counterpart
following the talks, Moussa told reporters that they discussed
over a working breakfast the importance of "the balanced roles"
Europe and the United States should play in the peace march.
</P>
<P>
"It is obvious that Europe does not want to limit itself to
just economic and financial aspects only, but it likes to play a
political role as well," Moussa added.
</P>
<P>
Mierlo, also Dutch deputy premier, said the EU has made great
efforts over the past few months in advancing the peace march,
referring to the presence of its special Mideast envoy Miguel
Angel Moratinos of Spain, who is due here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos did a good job during the talks, leading to the
executive protocol of the Hebron deal, Mierlo said at the end of a
two-day visit to Egypt, a part of his Mideast tour.
</P>
<P>
Mierlo accentuated that Europe would complement the U.S. role
for propelling the Mideast peace process since the latter has
played a definitive role since a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the U.S. should avoid playing its role in the
interests of Israel only, while Europe should also shun
supporting Palestine alone.
</P>
<P>
"The Americans were not at first enthusiastic about accepting a
European role in the process but they, and also the Israelis, have
fully accepted us," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Criticizing the Israeli settlement policies, the Dutch
official said that the EU believes it has a negative impact on
the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
