<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Acid Spill Kills Five in Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The spill of sulfuric acid
from a Mongolian-U.S. joint venture copper smeltery has so far
killed five people in the north central part of the country.
</P>
<P>
The spill, from Erdemi Copper Smeltery in Orhon Province,
happened last Wednesday, a day before the 14-million-dollar joint
venture came into production, said local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
However, the smeltery's management allegedly covered up the
incident and secured the participation of government officials in
a ceremony the next day for kicking up the facility's operation.
</P>
<P>
The acid eventually spilled up to 6 kilometers from the site
and caused severe damage to the environment and human health,
prompting the local government to impose a state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
The joint venture was designed to produce 3,000-6,000 tons of
pure copper a year by using locally available ore resources, so as
to start up Mongolia as a copper producing nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
