<HEADLINE> Shanghai Sets Economic Targets for This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
industrial city, will enhance its reform and opening-up this year,
Mayor Xu Kuangdi said today in a working report to the Municipal
People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu, Shanghai expects a 10-percent increase in the
gross domestic product this year, based on last year's 287.78
billion yuan (some 35.9 billion US dollars), and the contribution
of the tertiary industry will exceed 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
The mayor's report also set economic growth targets for the
municipality's total industrial output, foreign trade volume,
retail price rises and the local revenue income, which are
respectively 14 to 15 percent, 10 percent, below six percent and
13 percent.
</P>
<P>
Xu said special efforts will be made to explore the growth
potential of new industrial products and the Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
"The growth rate for the GDP in Pudong should be ensured at
over 18 percent," Xu said. 
</P>
