<HEADLINE> EU Assures Philippines of Stable Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
assured the Philippine government that the recent controversial
decision by the Supreme Court over the Manila Hotel privatization
project will not affect European investments in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Foreign Department confirmed today that during a
recent visit to Manila, two EU representatives gave the assurance
that the Manila Hotel controversy will not affect their existing
as well as planned future investments in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Supreme Court nullified the winning bid
of a Malaysian firm to purchase the Manila Hotel and ordered the
government to sell the hotel to a Philippine bidder.
</P>
<P>
The high tribunal ruled that the hotel belongs to the country's
heritage and should not be alienated to foreign control.
</P>
<P>
The decision sparked a controversy and a spate of protest from
the local and international business communities as well as the
Philippine government itself.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos even suggested convening Congress as a
constituent assembly to propose amendments to the charter that
will define and limit the judiciary's intrusion into the country's
economic policies.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Department has tried to explain the controversial
decision to the foreign business community, allaying fears of a
worsening investment environment in the country.
</P>
<P>
The EU is the third largest investor in the Philippines after
Japan and the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
