<HEADLINE> Beijing to Enhance City Management (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By the end of 1996, there were 1.1 million motorized vehicles
in the capital, up 93.9 percent over the figure of 1990. And
regular traffic jams are reported on 99 areas on the roads in
urban and suburban areas, a report from the traffic management
department shows.
</P>
<P>
The major reasons for the tie-ups are that the construction of
roads cannot keep up with the increase in vehicles, the number of
traffic violations is rising, and traffic management is flawed.
</P>
<P>
Jia said that the city will develop the public transportation
system this year by increasing the number of buses, establishing
suitable driving lines for buses and giving them priority to pass
through some busy intersections.
</P>
<P>
He said that the city will strengthen the management of
mini-bus and taxi companies, and urge them to improve their
services.
</P>
<P>
The city should improve its anti-disaster system, with the
focus on floods, earthquake and fire prevention, Jia noted.
</P>
<P>
The anti-disaster work should emphasize reinforcing the dams of
Miyun Reservoir and dredging the Yongding and Tonghui rivers to
guarantee a safe anti-flood system for the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Anti-quake knowledge and information on fighting and preventing
fires should be spread among residents, he noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
