<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Enhance City Management (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will take measures to
improve the management of the city's floating population, solve
the persistent problem of traffic jams and upgrade the
anti-disaster system this year, the city's acting mayor Jia
Qinglin said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the ongoing Fifth Session of the city's Tenth
People's Congress, Jia said that tightening the control of the
floating population should be placed at the top of the agenda, as
the number of the people in the city who are not Beijing residents
has gone above three million.
</P>
<P>
He said that the total number of the migrant workers should be
brought under control, while the regulations on employing them
should be closely observed and the illegal labor market be wiped
out.
</P>
<P>
Better management should be in place to supervise the living
areas of the migrants, peddlers in the open-air markets and
markets for agricultural products should be required to hold
business licenses, and the public security departments and
neighborhood communities should keep a close watch over the
temporary residents, Jia said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that in 1997, Beijing will ease the traffic
congestion through a unified traffic management system. People who
violate traffic regulations will be punished according to law, and
the total number of vehicles will be limited.
</P>
</TEXT>
