<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Join OECD Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines is likely to
formally join the Organization of Economic Cooperation for
Development (OECD) in the next two months, the Foreign Department
said today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the country is considering joining the
OECD because the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank
have already removed the country from the list of poor countries
and asked it to consider the status of donor nations.
</P>
<P>
The department said the Philippines, which has always been a
user of the OECD funds, now has to graduate to the ranks of the
group's "dynamic" members.
</P>
<P>
The OECD is a group of highly industrialized and developed
countries, which studies and monitors the economic development of
other countries and have their economies likewise monitored by
fellow members.
</P>
<P>
Members of the group are also regular sources of its
development funds provided to developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Among the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN),
Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore are already OECD members. The
Philippines will be the fourth ASEAN member to join the OECD.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
