<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portuguese President Confident of Macao's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese President Jorge
Sampaio said here tonight that he is "fully confident" of Macao's
future after China resumes its exercise of sovereignty over Macao.
</P>
<P>
The president made these remarks at a grand reception held at
the Macao Governor's Palace for his six-day visit to Macao
before his week-long official tour to Beijing next week.
</P>
<P>
"Macao owns a distinguished political structure, has good
relations with neighboring regions... and is also capable of
cultivating relationship with the European Union and the United
States," he said. "Macao will not only have new government, but
also enjoy its regional and international status set aside in the
Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration."
</P>
<P>
"Macao will thus enjoy greater prosperity and political and
social stability in the 21st century," he said.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Macao, the president is scheduled to meet
with top officials of the Macao government, heads of local leading
communities, and director of the Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch,
Wang Qiren. He will also host the opening ceremony of a number of
public facilities.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time for Sampaio to visit Macao after he took
office as Portuguese president last year. He is expected to
discuss a wide range of issues concerning the transition of Macao
and Sino-Portuguese relations with Chinese leaders during his
upcoming first visit to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
China and Portugal maintain good relations since the two sides
established diplomatic relations in 1979. Under the
Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration on the Question of Macao, China
will resume its exercise of sovereignty over Macao as of December
20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Sampaio said that both Portugal and China want a successful
transition in Macao, thus stepping up their cooperation now and in
the future.
</P>
<P>
"Macao will play an important role in the bilateral cooperative
relations (between Portugal and China)," said Sampaio. "It is the
historical destination for Macao and both peoples are glad to see
it that way."  
</P>
</TEXT>
