<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Decides to Advance Construction In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel decided today to
step up road construction in Jerusalem in an attempt to support
its assertion that the city is united and exclusively its eternal
capital.
</P>
<P>
The discussion of the sensitive construction issue regarding
the city at today's metting of the Ministerial Committee on
Jerusalem Affairs was proposed by Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu, according to a committee communique.
</P>
<P>
The committee decided to advance the construction of Highway 45
and Highway 4 which connects Jerusalem with Highway 45.
</P>
<P>
The committee also decided to accelerate the processes
regarding both the outline and the detailed plans for
constructing the Eastern Ring Road in Jerusalem, including the
Mt. Scopus road.
</P>
<P>
The planning for Highway 80 will also be advanced, said
the communique.
</P>
<P>
The construction in Jerusalem is always sensitive to the
Palestinians who claim East Jerusalem as the capital of their
future independent state.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has recently come under fierce attacks from inside
his rightwing coalition for not immediately advancing
construction of Jewish settlement in Har Homa, south Jerusalem,
after Hebron agreement.
</P>
<P>
Ze'ev Begin, Likud Member of Knesset, declared that he will
submit to a Knesset (parliament) plenum an urgent motion of no
confidence on what he called "The Dangers of Dividing Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that during his recent visit to the United
States, he reiterated Israel's "policy of insisting on our
sovereignty over all parts of Jerusalem and ensuring the unity and
security of the city."
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports, Netanyahu promised
U.S. President Bill Clinton that Israel would not resume
construction of Jewish settlement in Har Homa for fear that it
should trigger a fresh wave of violence.
</P>
<P>
General Security Service (GSS) head Ami Ayalon reportedly
warned the cabinet that a decision to build at Har Homa could lead
to what he called a "difficult reaction" by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Ayalon made a similar warning before the government opened the
tunnel in East Jerusalem last September. In the following days of
bloodshed violence, 61 Palestinians and 15 Israelis were
killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
