<HEADLINE> China's Capital City Persists In Opening Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- China's capital city will
continue to open its door wider to overseas investors and promote
foreign trade, Beijing Acting Mayor Jia Qinglin said during the
Fifth Session of the Tenth Municipal People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Jia said in his report on government work to the session that
opening up is the fundamental state policy that China will abide
by now and in the future, and that the city will make the most of
domestic and overseas markets in a bid to push its opening up to a
new level.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the city will give priority to the investment
of the transnational corporations with advanced technology and
high management level.
</P>
<P>
Projects involving hi-tech, urban infrastructure and housing
should be stressed in the process of attracting overseas
investment, Jia said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that different measures should be adopted for bringing
in such funds, such as issuing bonds and stocks on the overseas
market and using overseas loans.
</P>
<P>
The capital city has received investment from over 90 countries
and areas over the past decade, with 12,689 overseas-funded firms
approved by the end of January. The direct overseas investment
amounted to 20.027 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Jia said that the city plans to further improve the regulations
and policies concerning overseas investors, upgrade the efficiency
of the government, and enhance the management of the
overseas-funded enterprises, in order to improve the city's
investment environment.
</P>
<P>
Beijing also will promote cooperation with Taiwan, Hong Kong
and Macao regions in trade and technology, Jia said, adding that
the capital will increase the export of hi-tech products.
</P>
</TEXT>
