<HEADLINE> Beijing's Acting Mayor Calls for Further Fight Against Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Beijing Acting Mayor Jia
Qinglin has vowed to continue the fight for a clean and honest
government.
</P>
<P>
At the Fifth Plenary Session of the Tenth Municipal People's
Congress which opened in Beijing on Monday, Jia noted that great
emphasis will be placed on the anti-corruption campaign in the new
year, as successes were achieved in the work in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in the first half of last year, the
reception fees for the local Party committees, governments and
legislature dropped by nine percent over the same 1995 period, and
similar charges for other 114 Party and governmental institutions
decreased by 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
The city also created a records system for 40 municipal-level
officials and 197 department chiefs who are permitted to use cars
for public events.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, 40 cases involving officials occupying
unauthorized public housing have been handled, and 128 apartments
and 1.31 million yuan (about 167, 400 US dollars) worth of housing
loans have been retrieved.
</P>
<P>
Also last year, 31,000 officials above division chief level
completed income reports, and some 3,100 officials handed over
gifts which were valued at 1.24 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Among the city's 3,556 state-owned enterprises, 3,390 have
adopted a reporting practice through which gifts must be turned in
to the high-level departments.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the discipline inspection authorities looked into
1,300-plus cases, including 460 big cases involving 14
department-level officials and 165 section chiefs.
</P>
<P>
Jia stressed that this year his government will focus on cases
of officials' unauthorized use of housing, use of public funds for
personal entertainment, and other unlawful activities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
