<HEADLINE> ISU to Make Decision over Figure Skating Scoring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The International Skating Union
(ISU) has ordered an immediate review of its judging system to
find a way to make results more understandable to the public.
</P>
<P>
The move, described by the ISU as historic, is a result of
confusion that surrounded the men's final at the European
championships in Paris last month.
</P>
<P>
"It is now time for a major review of the placing system," said
ISU president Ottavio Cinquanta in a press release from the winter
council meetings in Cape Town, South Africa last week.
</P>
<P>
"Figure skating is an extremely technical sport and it is not
realistic to expect the public to be familiar with the complex but
necessary rules.
</P>
<P>
"However, it is crucial that the public can easily understand
how our sport is judged and we must develop a fair and
comprehensible system."
</P>
<P>
The current judging system is based on placements of skaters in
the short and free programmes of the event.
</P>
<P>
The ISU's figure skating and ice dance technical committees
will conduct feasibility studies into alternative placing systems
and submit a report to the ISU council at its next meeting in
Prague in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
