<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Carlos Hold Talks on Mideast Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 18 (Xinhua) -- King of Spain Juan Carlos, who
is on his second visit here in 20 years, met with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak today over bilateral relations,
Euro-Egyptian ties and the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The extended session of talks were attended by Egyptian Prime
Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa and his
Spanish counterpart Abel Matutes Y Juan, said the Egyptian MENA
news agency.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the talks, Moussa told reporters that contacts
held by Egypt with the EU should give a complementary push to the
peace march and to the U.S. role as well.
</P>
<P>
Moussa stressed the importance for the two sides to interact so
that the peace process may "bear fruit and have a sound outcome,
which does not tilt in favor of one party at the detriment of
another."
</P>
<P>
Moussa said Mubarak and Carlos also exchanged views on the
Mediterranean policy and cooperation within the framework of the
Mediterranean forum and the Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
King Carlos opened the Madrid Peace Conference in 1991 which
brought the Arabs and the Israelis to the negotiating table and
set the land-for-peace formulas as the basis for regional peace.
</P>
<P>
King Carlos arrived here Monday night, accompanied by a
50-member strong businessmen delegation, representing major
industrial companies in the southwestern European country.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Spain signed a cooperation and coordination accord at
the start of the four-day visit of King Juan Carlos Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The accord between the industries federations of both countries
provides for promoting direct contacts between companies in the
two countries and the development of bilateral trade relations.
</P>
<P>
During his four-day stay here, Carlos will attend a seminar on
trade exchange, joint investment and privatization in both
countries to be held on the fringe of the visit.
</P>
<P>
On the fringe of the visit, the Spanish businessmen will meet
their Egyptian counterparts to explore economic and trade
cooperation opportunities and boost joint projects.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade exchange between the two countries stands
only at 500 million dollars, with the trade balance tilting in
favor of Spain.
</P>
<P>
Spain invests over 85 million dollars in nine projects in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed an agreement on economic and industrial
cooperation in March 1991, an agreement on investment protection
and an agreement to avoid dual taxation in November 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
