<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Vows to Take Steps to Curb Smoking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Public Health Minister Chen
Minzhang today called on the whole nation to be more aware of the
hazards of smoking, take forceful measures to limit the number of
tobacco advertisements, and discourage smoking among young people.
</P>
<P>
Chen told a meeting of the organizing committee for the Tenth
World Conference on Tobacco or Health that his ministry will
launch a massive campaign to publicize the dangers of smoking to
encourage more people to kick the habit.
</P>
<P>
The conference will be held in Beijing from August 24-28, with
more than 1,800 participants from over 130 countries and regions
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Themed "Tobacco: Gradually Spreading Pestilence," the meeting
will focus discussions on world trends of tobacco use and
strategies to control the popularity of smoking.
</P>
<P>
A large exhibition will be staged during the conference to
display the achievements of smoking control campaigns.
</P>
<P>
China is a major tobacco producer in the world and has 300
million smokers. A recent survey shows that the number of smokers
in the country has increased, and many of them are young people.
</P>
<P>
A sample survey conducted by Liu Boqi, a professor from the
tumor research institute under the Chinese Academy on Medical
Sciences shows that lung cancer is the deadliest form of the
disease among people in cities with a population over one million,
and 70 to 80 percent of the cases have been caused by smoking,
according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the diseases that now have the
strongest influence on the health of Chinese people are
angiocardiopathy, tumors, high blood pressure and diabetes, and
tobacco use greatly contributes to these illnesses.
</P>
<P>
So far, six provinces and municipalities, along with 40 other
small and medium-sized cities in the country, have enacted laws
and regulations to prohibit smoking in public places.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Public Health and China's Association for
Smoking and Health are working jointly to create non-smoking
schools and to ban tobacco ads in cities in the coming years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
