<HEADLINE> Mexican Foreign Minister Visits Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Mexican Foreign Minister
Jose Angel de Gurria toured Hebron this morning, becoming the
first senior foreign official to visit the city since Israel
withdrew from most part of the West Bank city last month.
</P>
<P>
Gurria began his tour with a visit to the Hebron
Municipality. He held talks there with Palestinian Minister of
Local Government Saeb Erekat and Hebron Mayor Mustafa Abdel Nabi
Natsheh.
</P>
<P>
The hosts briefed the guest on the current political
and economic situation in the Palestinian territories and the
daily hardships suffered by the local residents stemming from
Jewish settlers and Israeli military authorities.
</P>
<P>
Gurria conveyed an invitation for Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat to visit Mexico. Arafat is now on a visit to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
He also informed Erekat of the Mexican government's decision
to recognize the Palestinian Passport/Travel Document. Gurria
said that the Mexican Embassy in Tel Aviv will be in
charge of coordination work with the Palestinian National
Authority on cooperation between Mexico and Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the visit, first ever by a Mexican government
minister to the Palestinian territories, Gurria had concluded a
two-day visit to Israel. He met with Prime minister Binyamin
Netanyahu and Foreign Minister David Levy separately Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
