<HEADLINE> Jordan Eyes France As Promising Market for Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Jordan received more than 30,000
French tourists in 1996, making France the third most important
European tourism market after the United Kingdom and Germany,
Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to 55 French tourism agents taking part in a five-day
promotional visit to Jordan, Jordanian Tourism and Antiquities
Minister Saleh Irsheidat stressed Monday that "tourism from France
has the potential to increase further and cover a higher share of
total arrivals from Europe."
</P>
<P>
Suleiman Tarazi, market and development manager at Jordan
Tourism Investment, said that "85 percent of our customers are
from Europe and the U.S., and French tourists account for a
significant share of this percentage."
</P>
<P>
Most of Jordan's tourists are from the Arab world, but the
negative perception of the country's stance during the Gulf crisis
deterred potential visitors from the Arab Gulf states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
