<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Has Over 7.34 Million Industrial Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- China has made clear with a
just-ended national industrial census its industry's scale,
efficiency and structure after tens years of groping in the dark.
</P>
<P>
The census, taken in 1996, revealed that at the end of 1995
China had 7.342 million industrial enterprises, 2.156 million more
than in 1985, when China's second national census was done.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1995, the enterprises employed 147 million
people, 56.8 percent more than in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Li Qiming, spokesman for the State Statistics Bureau, told a
press conference today that the value-added output of the Chinese
industry grew at an annual rate of 13.4 percent during the span of
ten years, adding the decade saw the quickest industrial
development since 1949, when New China was founded.
</P>
<P>
The census found that China had 118,000 state-owned enterprises
at the end of 1995, 24,000 more than in 1985 and the state-owned
enterprises (SOEs) continued to serve as the backbone of the
national industry in the ten years.
</P>
<P>
"Their total asset was valued at 4,747.2 billion yuan,
accounting for 53.7 percent of the national industrial total," he
said. "The rate, which was 74.6 percent in 1985, dropped annually
by 2.1 percentage points."
</P>
<P>
However, he said, SOEs enjoy dominant positions in petroleum
and natural gas mining, coal gas production and supply, oil
refining, tap water development and supply, wood and bamboo
felling and transportation, as well as some important energy and
raw materials industries.
</P>
<P>
Expounding the difficulties of the SOEs, the spokesman said
that the Chinese state industry's assets-liability ratio stood at
65.8 percent at the end of 1995, higher than most of
industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
He said that SOEs also suffered a heavy social burden and that
last year they paid 60.38 billion yuan in retirement and welfare
funds, which accounted for 15 percent of their profit.
</P>
<P>
The census also found that China had 59,311 overseas-funded
industrial enterprises, which employed 8.993 million people, at
the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that oversees investment mainly convergeed in
coastal regions in and that overseas investment in the five provinces
and autonomous regions accounted for less than one percent of the
total.
</P>
<P>
"The overseas investors also tended to crowd in electronics,
telecommunications equipment, textile and food processing
industries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said that Chinese workers' competency has also improved in the
ten years.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1995, engineers and technicians accounted for six
percent of the staff in the Chinese industry. The rate marked a
rise of 3.2 percentage points from 1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
