<HEADLINE> Malaysia Wants U.N. Veto Power Reviewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today called for
a review of the veto power in the United Nations Security Council
to provide for any decision to be vetoed by at least two of its
five permanent members instead of one as practiced so far.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said that Malaysia and
some other U.N. members who shared Kuala Lumpur's view in this
matter feel that the veto power is only effective when two
permanent members exercise the right and not only one.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah made the remarks after a meeting with visiting
U.S. Acting Assistant Secretary of State for International
Organization Affairs Princeton Lyman.
</P>
<P>
Lyman, however, expressed Washington's objection to such
review. "The U.S. would not want to see a change in the veto of
the permanent members. We think it (the veto) is not much of a
problem as, perhaps, in the past."
</P>
<P>
He said the Security Council had become effective lately and
there had been little use of the veto power because there was a
great deal of pressure on everyone to be cooperative and
effective. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
