<HEADLINE> China Maintains Tax Rebate Policy Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- China plans no major changes
to its policy on export tax rebates this year, according to a
senior taxation official.
</P>
<P>
"Both the rebate rates and the system will remain largely
unchanged this year," said Cheng Faguang, deputy-director of the
State Administration of Taxation (SAT).
</P>
<P>
"If the policies and detailed operation rules are changed, they
will only be made even more to benefit the interest of exporters,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Cheng also said that China will pay all the delayed tax rebates
to exporters by the end of this year, as dictated by a State
Council decision at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The SAT will work together with other government departments to
formulate a set of rules on tax exemptions and rebates for
manufacturers that export goods on their own, he said.
</P>
<P>
The rules will be implemented after State Council approval, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Official figures showed that Chinese exporters were paid 82.63
billion yuan (about 9.9 billion US dollars) in tax rebates last
year, up 50.5 percent over 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
