<HEADLINE> Concern over Moody's Downgrade Dents Thai Bourse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Investors' concern about a
possible downgrade in Thailand's sovereign debt rating and the
effects of a strengthening U.S. dollar sent the Stock Exchange of
Thailand (SET) index further down by 8.05 points or 1.1 percent
today.
</P>
<P>
The SET index closed at 700.15 points today, following a slide
of 5.28 points Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said no one knew how much further the index would fall
and that the overall sentiment remained bearish, with many
investors still digesting news that Thailand's A2 long-term debt
rating, assigned by Moody's Investors Services, is subject to a
review for possible downgrade.
</P>
<P>
The announcement had helped send the SET index down to a low
664.45 points earlier Friday.
</P>
<P>
The mid-rate Monday was set by the Central Bank of Thailand at
25.99 baht to the U.S. dollar, up one satang from last trading
day.
</P>
<P>
The market still doubted the Thai baht's stability.  
</P>
</TEXT>
