<HEADLINE> Iraqi Minister Accuses UN of Delaying Food Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 18 (Xinhua) - Iraqi Minister of Trade Mohammad
Mehdi Salsh has accused the United Nations Sanctions Committee of
delaying the approval of agreements Iraq has signed for the
supply of food and medicine, Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Salsh made the remarks Monday in an interview with the paper
before leaving here for Cairo, Egypt, to attend an Arab meeting.
</P>
<P>
Salsh said Iraq has already concluded orders for importing
products under the oil-for-food deal with the U.N. from eight
countries, including the United States, France, Jordan and
five other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Salsh said the U.N. Sanctions Committee has been
"unjustifiably" delaying the implementation of these contracts,
inflicting losses on exporters, including those from Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Iraq expected the first shipment of wheat, rice and milk under
the U.N. deal to arrive in Iraq in the second half of March and
the Trade Ministry will distribute the food supplies in April in
accordance with a government plan, said Salsh.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had decided to import food via Jordanian port Aqaba and
nearly 300,000 tonnes of food supplies will be arriving through
the port, earning Jordan nearly 15 million U.S. dollars in service
fees, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Salsh stressed that Iraq's stand towards Jordan remains
unchanged and "good" Iraqi-Jordanian relations were helping Iraq
maintain its steadfastness in the face of economic embargo.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Sanctions Committee experts last Thursday agreed on a way
to speed up the approval of food and medicine contracts. Up to now,
only four of the 153 export orders have been approved by the
committee.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal, Iraq can export 2 billion
dollars of oil over six months to pay for food and medicine as
well as to defray U.N. costs and war reparations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
