<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Major Dams Spilling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Most of Zimbabwe's dams now
have spilled, leaving some villagers stranded because of
flooding, the country's national news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said of the 57 inland dams, 40 are over 90 percent
full, with 34 already spilling.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has experienced over seven weeks of continuous rains
with major dams now recording a combined capacity of over 82.19
percent, latest government statistics on the state of major dams
show.
</P>
<P>
The spilling of major dams has left families stranded and
schools closed in some parts of Mashonaland Central, Manicaland
and Midlands Provinces, as homes and schools were swept away by
floods.
</P>
<P>
The spills are however good news for urban local authorities
like Harare and other urban centers whose supply dams and water
reservoirs are 100 percent full, assuring water supply for the
next two and half years.
</P>
<P>
The news agency also reported that elsewhere in the southern
African region, tens of thousands of people have been left
homeless in Malawi, Mozambique and South Africa by flooding.
</P>
<P>
In Malawi and Mozambique, which share the same rivers as they
run east toward the Indian Ocean, food and blankets have been
air dropped to villages isolated by floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
