<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portuguese President Arrives in Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese President Jorge
Sampaio said today that he is confident that the model set by the
Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration will be implemented and the
transitional affairs proceed smoothly.
</P>
<P>
He made these remarks upon his arrival here this afternoon
prior to his week-long official tour to Beijing from February 23.
He is going to stay in Macao for six days.
</P>
<P>
The Portuguese president said in a short speech at the Macao
International Airport that his current visit to Macao is aimed to
know Macao more directly and the expectations of Macao residents.
</P>
<P>
Sampaio said he is confident that the current characteristics
and life style of the region will remain unchanged in the future.
</P>
<P>
All administrative organs of the (Portuguese) Republic "will
continue to pay attention to and make great efforts on the Macao
affairs," said the president. "So that the region will have
stability, safety, prosperity and freedom."
</P>
<P>
He urged all sides to make efforts so that the high autonomy
set aside by the Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration will be
exercised.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Macao, he will meet top officials of the
Macao government, heads of local leading communities, and Director
of the Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch Wang Qiren. He will also
host the opening ceremony of a number of public facilities.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time for Sampaio to visit Macao and Beijing
after he took office as Portuguese president in March last year.
He is expected to discuss a wide range of issues concerning the
transition of Macao and Sino-Portuguese relations with Chinese
leaders.
</P>
<P>
China and Portugal maintain good relations since the two sides
established diplomatic relations in 1979. Under the
Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration on the Question of Macao, China
will resume its exercise of sovereignty over Macao as of December
20, 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
