<HEADLINE> China Travel Firms Invest in Road Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 18 (Xinhua) -- China Travel Service Hong
Kong (CTS) has struck a joint venture with Coastal International
for transport projects in the Chinese mainland, according to local
reports today.
</P>
<P>
CTS and its listed arm, China Travel International Investment
(CTII) Hong Kong, held a combined 51 percent of the new venture,
CTS-Coastal Investment (CCI).
</P>
<P>
The venture signed its first project yesterday -- an
acquisition of a 60-percent stake in the Tianjin section of the
Beijing-Shanghai Expressway.
</P>
<P>
CCI will invest some 800 million yuan (96 million US dollars)
in the 1.36 billion yuan (163 million US dollars) project.
</P>
<P>
The road is expected to start charging toll in late 1997 upon
its partial completion. The project will be finished by mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
CCI is also interested in power projects and other
transportation related businesses, said Xu Shiquan, director and
deputy general manager of CTS.
</P>
<P>
CTII director Zheng Hongqing said they intended to spin off the
joint venture for a separate listing within the next three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
