<HEADLINE> FIFA President Recommends Beckenbauer as Successor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- FIFA President Joao Havelange
said in Zurich Tuesday that Franz Beckenbauer of Germany would
appear to be an ideal candidate to succeed him in his post in
1998, according to reports from Zurich.
</P>
<P>
The 80-year-old Brazilian, in his post for the last 23 years,
announced last December he would not stand for another term after
the World Cup in France next year.
</P>
<P>
Havelange said: "Beckenbauer was a great player, a wonderful
coach, a successful businessman and president of one of the great
footballing powers in Europe. So why shouldn't he be a candidate
as he has all the requirements to do the job."
</P>
<P>
Havelange's support for Beckenbauer has been echoed by the
former Brazilian master and minister of sport Pele.
</P>
<P>
Havelange also confirmed that he would not reconsider standing
again even if the candidates to replace him did not meet with his
approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
