<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Executive Council Starts Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Executive Council of the
first government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) held the first official meeting today since it was formed
on January 24.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, the first Chief Executive of HKSAR, presided
over the three-hour meeting this morning. Nine out of 14 members
of the HKSAR Executive Council were present to mainly discuss on
the rules of procedure, which are essential to the operation of
the advisory body.
</P>
<P>
The absentees from today's meeting include three official
members --Administrative Secretary, Financial Secretary and
Secretary of Justice -- whom the Chief Executive has not nominated
and reported to the central government for appointment.
</P>
<P>
Raymond Ch'ien Kuo-fung, and Rosanna Wong Yick-ming, both
incumbent Executive Councilors of the Hong Kong British government
will not attend the HKSAR Executive Council meeting until July 1,
1997, according to Tung.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing after the meeting, Tung said that
nominations for the principal officials of the HKSAR have gone
into the final stage. He expected to announce the results at the
weekend after a one-day trip to Beijing on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, the constitutional document for the
future HKSAR, the Executive Council is an organ for assisting the
Chief Executive in policy-making. The Chief Executive shall
consult the Executive Council before making important policy
decisions, introducing bills to the Legislative Council, making
subordinate legislation, or dissolving the Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
Following the inaugural meeting, the HKSAR Executive Council
will convene every Tuesday, said Tung.  
</P>
</TEXT>
