<HEADLINE> Conference on Drug Education in Schools Opens in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Overseas Representatives
attending the International Conference on Drug Education in
Schools today shared Hong Kong's experience in the prevention of
drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Hong Kong Education Department, the two-day
meeting starting here today is the first of its kind ever held in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Director of Education, Mrs. Helen C P Lai Yu, said her
department has taken steps to promote preventive education in
support of the multi-facet campaign mounted by the government to
beat drugs.
</P>
<P>
"We have integrated elements of drug education into our school
curriculum to bring out the harmful effects of drug abuse," she
said.
</P>
<P>
At least one teacher has been trained in every secondary school
on drug education, she noted.
</P>
<P>
The department also operates a Drug Education Resources Center
to give schools advice and support, Mrs. Yu said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the department has mounted roving exhibitions to
enhance the awareness of the problem of drug abuse and provided
grants for schools and parent-teacher associations to organize
drug education projects.
</P>
<P>
Educational camps for students and young people have also been
organized to spread anti-drug messages and to provide healthy
pastimes, she added.
</P>
<P>
Some 250 local educators and experts from Japan, China, the
Philippines, Canada, as well as some other countries and regions,
participated in the conference.  
</P>
</TEXT>
