<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Citibank Moves to Shanghai's Pudong for Yuan Business Eds: More details added </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Citibank of the United States
on Monday became the first overseas bank to move its Shanghai
branch to the city's Pudong New Area to qualify for business in
the Chinese currency.
</P>
<P>
Citibank is making preparations for yuan-based services, though
the Shanghai branch of the People's Bank of China, the central
bank, is still drawing up operational guidelines and tax
structures for overseas banks selected to deal in yuan-based
business on a trial basis, said John Beeman, Citibank's chief
representative for China.
</P>
<P>
"We can handle yuan-based loans and deposits, provide
guarantees and settlements, and deal in Chinese treasury and
financial bonds once the operational rules are formulated and we
pass Chinese financial regulatory examinations," Beeman said.
</P>
<P>
"It won't take a long time and I expect our bank to be able to
do yuan business first in April," he said.
</P>
<P>
Citibank is one of eight foreign banks that have been approved
by China's central bank to deal in the local currency on a trial
basis in Pudong, an emerging financial and trade zone separated
from downtown Shanghai by the Huangpu River.
</P>
<P>
Citibank has the biggest business network among all American
banks in China. It also has branches in Beijing and Shenzhen and
representative offices in Guangzhou and Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
The other seven approved overseas banks are the Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd., the Industrial Bank of Japan, Hongkong and
Shanghai Banking Corporation, Daiichi Kangyo Bank of Japan, Sanwa
Bank of Japan, the British Standard Chartered bank, and the
International Bank of Paris and Shanghai, a joint-venture between
France's Banque Nationale de Paris and the Industrial and
Commercial Bank of China, China's largest commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
Overseas banks given licences for yuan business can only
operate in Shanghai and their clients are limited to
overseas-funded enterprises and overseas individuals.
</P>
<P>
Chinese rules also stipulate that the amount of foreign banks'
yuan liabilities is capped at 35 percent of their debt in foreign
exchange and they must follow interest rate policies for Chinese
banks.
</P>
<P>
Overseas banks must relocate their Shanghai branches to Pudong
as a qualification for yuan business, though they are permitted to
retain sub-branches in Puxi, as east Shanghai is known, to provide
foreign currency services.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the restrictions, Beeman said he is confident in
Citibank's prospects in yuan business.
</P>
<P>
He explained that Citibank's experience in local currency
business in more than 130 countries and regions will enable it to
make profits in China.
</P>
<P>
He added that Citibank, which has become a major clearing bank
for the US dollar at the Shanghai-based China Foreign Exchange
Trade System, plans to upgrade its Guangzhou office to a branch
and set up more representative offices in other Chinese cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6 Countries to Discuss Zaire Crisis in Kinshasa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministers of South
Africa, Tanzania and Kenya left here today for Kinshasa to
discuss the crisis of Great Lakes region with Zairean government
leaders.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Kenyan Foreign Minister Kalonzo Musyoka
at a press conference here today before their departure.
</P>
<P>
Musyoka said that foreign ministers from Zimbabwe, Cameroun
and Congo, and representative of the Organization of African
unity would join them in discussions in the Zairean capital.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the main agenda of the Kinshasa
meeting is to examine possibilities of holding a third Heads of
State summit in Nairobi to discuss the deteriorating Great Lakes
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is a follow-up to another foreign ministers
meeting held recently in Pretoria, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Two Heads of State summits sponsored by Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi were held last year in Nairobi to seek solutions
to the burning crisis in eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
In view of the deteriorating situation in eastern Zaire,
President Moi appealed on February 12 to the United Nations, the
United States and the European Union to provide a force to act as
a buffer between Zaire and its neighbors, meaning Uganda, Rwanda
or Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Zaire accuses the three Great Lakes countries of Backing its
rebels who took up arms to fight last October. But these
countries have denied involvement.
</P>
<P>
However, Ugandan President Y. Museveni recently hinted that
since Kinshasa backs the Hutu rebels to fight Kigali, maybe
Rwanda has supported the Tutsi rebels in eastern Zaire to fight
for their right of existence. The Tutsis are part of the rebels
who have now vow to topple the regime in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Kenyan leader called for an immediate
stop by countries fuelling the armed conflict in eastern Zaire by
being directly involved in or supplying combatants with weapons.
</P>
<P>
In January, he also urged the rebels in eastern Zaire to move
out of occupied towns of Goma, Bukavu and Uvira to avoid a
looming war.
</P>
<P>
Moi noted that when the rebels move out of these towns, it
would enable international community to seek solutions to the
crisis without further bloodshed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
