<HEADLINE> Britain Denies "Deliberately Burning Down" Benin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 18 (Xinhua) -- British government on Monday
denied "deliberately burning down" the ancient Benin city in
today's Edo State of Nigeria, when its troops invaded the Bini
kingdom in 1897.
</P>
<P>
Today's "Daily Champion" quoted the British higher
commissioner to Nigeria, Thorold Masefield as saying this at the
opening of the one-week commemorative activities marking the
centenary of the British invasion.
</P>
<P>
According to the high commissioner, the fire which destroyed
the roofs of many of the houses in Benin started "accidently",
not deliberately.
</P>
<P>
He ackowledged that the British took away treasures of the
Benin people, but explained that they did not remove all "but
only those half buried in the palace."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prince of Benin, Edun Akenzua has made a
renewed call on the British government to return the treasures
that were carted away a centuray ago to benin.
</P>
<P>
On his return from a recent Europe visit, the prince said
earlier that the British parliament is considering the
possibility of entertaining a bill that would faciliate the
return of the stolen artifacts. 
</P>
