<HEADLINE> Regional Meeting on Environment of Lake Victoria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 18 (Xinhua) -- A consultative meeting on
Lake Victoria's environment management is scheduled to open today
in Kisumu, west Kenya, the Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
Local community Participation in the 24.3-million-U.S.-Dollar
project, funded by the World Bank, is on top of the agenda of the
two-day meeting to be attended by delegates from the World Bank,
donor countries, governments of Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania, as
well as some non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
The report said the local non-governmental organizations
objected to the idea that the central government should control
the funds through the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
A Kisumu-based environmental organization named OSIENALA,
organizer of the meeting, has been advocating the community
participation approach to the environmental issues of Lake
Victoria.
</P>
<P>
Lake Victoria, the world's second largest freshwater lake, is
facing a number of ecological threats, particularly the
fast-spreading weed of water hyacinth.
</P>
<P>
A comprehensive report on the current status of the lake
revealed that its resources were being squandered, warning that
unless preventive actions are taken immediately, the livelihood
of close to 30 million people in the region would hang in the
balance.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has agreed to provide, through the channel of
the Global Environment Facility, about 70 million U.S. Dollars to
Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania for the Lake Victoria Environmental
Program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
