<HEADLINE> Uganda Army Raids Suspected Rebel Camp in East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 18 (XINHUA) -- Uganda army raided a
suspected rebel camp, killed one, captured a dozen of them in the
East, "the Monitor" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Uganda People's Defence Forces (UPDE) encircled the camp in a
forest in eastern Iganda district, and launched the operation
earlier last Friday, security sources said.
</P>
<P>
The government detachmont killed one suspect and wounded other
two in a crossfire, and arrested still another four at the scene,
the report said, adding that the whole area was sealed, and the
government detachment captured six in a following mop up
operation on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said the detachment also captured a batch of
ammunitions and arms.
</P>
<P>
The operation was launched since authority arrested last
Thursday a suspected spy of Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) in
Iganga town. The suspect was said to have revealed the existence
of an estimated 50-men camp in the forest. He later led three
trucks of government troops to the scene.
</P>
<P>
Local residents said UPDF was continuing its mop up operation
in the area Saturday and the traffic was blocked in the area.
</P>
<P>
Earlier unconfirmed reports said LRA had sent its members late
last year to eastern Uganda to recruit young people for training
and to spread rebellion. Scatterred reports from the district of
Iganda said that there were activities of armed gangs from late
last year. But colonel Fred Tolit, the director of military
intelligence, said he did not know any rebellion in Iganda, "you
must differentiate between a rebel, a thug and a bandit" he said
yesterday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
