<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: Liberalization, Double-Edged Sword for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Liberalization of the market
for maize, soybean and fishmeal can be a double-edged sword for
the economy and the Thai government faces a tough decision.
</P>
<P>
Last year, under its commitments to the World Trade
Organization (WTO) the Thai government announced liberalization of
imports of soybean meal and maize, with no import quotas. Maize
can be imported from February 20 to June 30 with no tariff on
condition that the domestic price must not be lower than 4.50 baht
(about 0.18 U.S. dollars) per kilogram. Outside this period the
tariff will be 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
There is no quota for imports of soybean meal but importers
must pay a 10 percent tariff and buy domestic soybeans at a
minimum price of 8.5 baht (0.34 dollars) per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
Liberalization of the market, which means free imports without
tariffs or quota, of maize, soybean and fishmeal, will benefit
manufacturers of animal feed and poultry raisers, as the move will
help them lower their production cost and increase their profit
margin.
</P>
<P>
However, local planters and fishmeal producers claim that they
will be hurt by the same move, as they have to reduce their prices
to compete with imported materials.
</P>
<P>
Despite the pros and cons of liberalization, the government has
shown its intention to promote the livestock and poultry
industries as more promising ways of improving the economy than
soybean, maize and fishmeal processing.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, livestock and poultry exports have been
important for the country's foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
Adul Srithem, president of the Agricultural and Cooperative
Community in Chiang Mai, said the government's commitment to the
WTO was implemented without proper preparation and has hurt
farmers.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the government's price-intervention schemes, saying
they were only short-term fixes. Instead, he said, the government
should invest more in improving farm productivity and reduce
dependence on imports.
</P>
<P>
From the government's point of view, however, the conclusion
can be the opposite.
</P>
<P>
Before deciding which is to be sacrificed, a long-term
consideration on which is to be promoted, is needed.
</P>
<P>
A short while ago, the House Committee on Agriculture was of
the opinion that the country's economy could be driven by
livestock and fisheries, so it recommended that the government
make the livestock sector a long-term priority.
</P>
<P>
As Thailand is less competitive as a soybean producer than
other countries, such as the U.S., Thailand should make long-term
plans to stop producing soybean.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the livestock industry firmly supported the
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
Animal feed is a significant cost factor in meat production and
the sector's feed consumption could increase 40 percent to 1.4
million tons in five years' time, according to Damrong Chianond,
president of the Thai Feedmeal Producers' Association.
</P>
<P>
The industry imports about two million tons of grains a year to
produce animal feed, and pays about 3 billion baht (120 million
U.S. dollars) in import tariffs.
</P>
<P>
If the market is liberalized as the government has committed,
the government could offer one more excuse for the farmers to
stage protest rallies.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of farmers have been outside the Government House for
weeks now to demand settlement of their problems, including low
farm prices, compensation of dam and public projects and land
rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
