<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hubei Improves Rural Health Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hubei Province
will set up a cooperative medical system and take a number of
other measures over the next 15 years to improve farmers' health,
the provincial governor Jiang zhuping has announced.
</P>
<P>
The province will push the co-op medical system to the rural
areas. Both farmers and the collectives will contribute designated
sums to form the medical fund.
</P>
<P>
All the farmers' medical expenditures for minor ailments will
be paid from the co-op monies, which will also cover most of the
costs for serious illnesses.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, the system will be introduced into most of
the rural areas in the province.
</P>
<P>
The medical organizations in urban areas will be required to
aid some of their counterparts in the countryside, and plans
should be made to help the 38 poor counties and train medical care
workers for those areas.
</P>
<P>
Steps should be taken to improve the hygiene standard of the
drinking water, spread the use of clean toilets and eliminate
snail fever, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The province will grant 15 percent of the social development
fund to improve the medical services at county, township and
village levels, Jiang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
