<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large-Scale Chinese Oil And Gas Exploration In Bohai Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- China is expecting a major
breakthrough in oil and gas exploration in the Bohai Sea this
year, with proven oil and gas reserves forecast at 60 million tons
and 10 billion cu m respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior official with the China National Offshore
Oil Corp. (CNOOC), the Bohai Oil Company, a subsidiary of CNOOC,
will be able to produce 4.5 million tons of crude oil by the year
2000, and ultimately 8.24 million tons by 2010.
</P>
<P>
CNOOC's experts noted that the Bohai Sea has an effective oil
and gas exploration area of 54,000 sq km, or about the same size
as the Dagang, Shengli, East Hebei, and Liaohe mainland oilfields
combined.
</P>
<P>
To date, the four oilfields have verified oil reserves of six
billion tons, with combined an annual output topping 50 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
The Bohai Sea area, which has a similar geological structure,
has verified only 500 million tons of oil and developed an annual
output of 2.1 million tons. In addition to the 500 million tons,
it still has three very promising exploration areas.
</P>
<P>
A depression in the central part of the Bohai, which has an
area of 8,660 sq km, is expected to produce 25 billion cu m of oil
and eight trillion cu m of gas in total, and is considered to be
the richest oil and gas bearing area in the Bohai.
</P>
<P>
The experts noted that there is also a gas bearing structure
extending from the western part to the southern part of the sea,
which is expected to have billions of cu m of gas.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a total of one billion tons of oil reserves have
been verified in an onshore part of the Liaoxi Depression and an
oilfield with proven oil reserves of 30 million tons as well as a
gasfield have been discovered in the offshore part of the
Depression.
</P>
<P>
The Bohai Sea area has enough oil reserve to develop an annual
crude output of eight million tons, the experts say.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Agrees to Import American Wheat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 18 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has agreed
to import United States wheat which had failed to fulfill its
sanitary requirement, local daily Business Report said today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on removing sanitary obstacles to trade was
reached on Monday during the meeting of the Agriculture Committee
of the South Africa-U.S. Bi-National Commission, co-chaired by
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and his American
counterpart Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has banned importing soft Durham wheat from
southwest U.S. for months because it has been infected with bunt,
a disease that could affect the quality of the wheat, though not
harmful to the human body.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day meeting, the two sides also agreed to
create mutually acceptable mechanisms for sanitary testing of
other food imports from both countries to overcome non-tariff
trade barriers.
</P>
<P>
Both Mbeki and Gore hailed the agreements as a "breakthrough"
for liberalizing bilateral trade in agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
Restrictions on sanitary reasons and disagreement on
non-tariff trade have caused obstacles in the trade of products
such as U.S. frozen pork and non-containerized chickens as well
as South African exports such as fresh fruit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
