<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Villages shelled by Israeli Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT (Xinhua) -- One civilian was killed and two others were
wounded this morning in a Israeli bombardment at villages in the
central sector of south Lebanon opposite an Israeli-occupied
border strip, police sources said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli artillery fired down at a number of villages from
a hilltop position overlooking the south Lebanese area of
Nabatiyeh this morning, within its daily aggressions against this
country, the police sources in the area reported.
</P>
<P>
Several shells hit the village of Habboush at 9:00 a.m.
(07 GMT) killing a 33-year-old woman, Naema Yousef Halal, and
wounding two others, the sources noted.
</P>
<P>
Damages were also caused to some a dozen of houses in
the village, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation for the Israeli bombardments, guerrillas of
the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, launched attacks at
Israeli positions of Dabbesheh, Soueida and Dhuhra, but no
casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
The civilian casualties were made after an international
committee monitoring a limited truce in the border area between
Lebanon and Israel ended a meeting in the south Lebanese
border town of Naqoura without denouncing any sides for
cease-fire breaches.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring committee comprising representatives of France,
Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the United States met in
headquarters of the U.N. peace-keeping forces at 11:00 a.m.
(0900 GMT) Monday to discuss complaints filed by Lebanon and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
After ending its meeting around the midnight, the committee
issued a statement urging all combating sides to respect the
terms of a cease-fire understanding Lebanon and Israel reached
in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the complaint lodged to the committee, Beirut wanted
Israel to be held accountable for the wounding of a shepherd
and damages to homes in the Beqaa during a string of Israeli
air attacks last week.
</P>
<P>
Israel lodged a counter claim after its forces discovered
five bombs planted within the occupied zone which they said
put civilians at risk.
</P>
<P>
The five-nation committee accepted as "factual" both claims
but issued no condemnations.
</P>
<P>
"In lights of these events, the monitoring group by unanimity
deemed it necessary to urge once more all combatants to abide
strictly and fully by the provisions of the understanding reached
on April 26, 1996 and exercise restraint and caution in military
operations in the vicinity of civilian populated areas," the
committee statement said.
</P>
<P>
The April understanding, under which the cease-fire monitoring
committee was set up, bars all the parties from targeting
civilians in their military operations.
</P>
<P>
However, the understanding does not impose a ban on
guerrilla attacks on Israeli occupation forces in south Lebanon
and gives the Israeli troops a right of "self-defense."
</P>
<P>
Hit-and-run attacks by Moslem guerrillas and bombardments by
Israeli forces constitute a daily scene on the last active
battlefront of the Arab Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1.100-square-kilometer "security zone" in
south Lebanon in 1985 in a bid to protect northern Israel
from crossing-border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0144 </DOCNO>
