<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Central Bank Takes Over Forex Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's central bank has
resumed its control over the foreign exchange earnings of the
state-owned Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) which earns
the country 80 percent of its foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
The government has, through a statutory instrument signed by
Minister of Finance and Economic Development, Ronald Penza,
ordered ZCCM not to dispose of its foreign exchange earnings but
to surrender it to the central bank, Bank of Zambia (BOZ), local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Six months ago, BOZ stopped handling foreign currency earnings
from ZCCM after another statutory instrument was issued allowing
ZCCM to offload almost 100 percent of its foreign currency
earnings onto the market.
</P>
<P>
Since then, ZCCM's foreign exchange earnings has been
immediately made available to the market following BOZ's
withdrawal from handling 45 percent of ZCCM's earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
