<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> University Students Work As Part-Time Postmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Teachers and students at a
leading university in northeast China had a hard time in the past
just posting or receiving letters, because the post office was so
far away.
</P>
<P>
Now, all they have to do is take a few steps from their
dormitories to a special letter box, established by a group of
"volunteer campus postmen".
</P>
<P>
"The idea of providing on-campus postal service for students
and teachers came to me in early 1993," recalled Xu Changpo, a
student in the Mechanics and Engineering College of Northeast
University in Shenyang, the capital of Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
With the support of the school administration, Xu formed a team
of volunteers consisting of 47 students with outstanding academic
records. "The members of our team must be academically good, so
that they have spare time and energy to serve others," Xu
explained.
</P>
<P>
The volunteers set up letter boxes near dormitories and
teachers' residences, which they check every day, rain or shine,
carrying letters to the post office, and delivering arriving
letters.
</P>
<P>
"Some letters fail to provide a clear address or name, and we
have to go from dorm to dorm to find the recipient," Xu noted.
"Sometimes we climb six to seven floors and knock at dozens of
doors."
</P>
<P>
During holidays and vacations, the volunteers usually ask those
remaining on campus to be substitutes, or even return earlier than
other students. Some have even given up the chance to go home.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, they have helped their schoolmates
and teachers send and receive more than 720,000 letters, without a
single missed letter.
</P>
<P>
"Almost everyone on campus knows us, and we've gotten a lot of
greetings and cards from our fellow students during festivals," Xu
said.
</P>
<P>
One New Year's Day card went like this: "While we are listening
to music or studying English in our warm dormitories, you are
braving the bitter cold of the winter evening and teaching us the
meaning of 'dedication'." 
</P>
</TEXT>
