<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany To Aid Chinese Lake Ecology Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The German government has
signed an agreement with north China's Hebei Province for 13
million Deutsche marks (about 8.9 million U.S. dollars) to help a
Baiyangdian Lake ecology project.
</P>
<P>
Baiyangdian is known as the "bright pearl of north China", but
has become seriously polluted as more factories are built near it.
</P>
<P>
The project calls for purification of lake water, planting
trees, and several other projects for ecological recovery of the
lake and nearby areas.
</P>
<P>
So far, Baoding City has removed 13 industrial polluters at a
cost of 44 million yuan (about 5.5 million dollars), and a waste
water disposal plant and coal ash waste plant in the lake area
went operational recently.
</P>
<P>
Anxin County, which is next to the lake, has put more than 1.2
million US dollars into rebuilding county roads, and building
better toilet facilities and garbage disposal areas.
</P>
<P>
The county also improved more than 400 diesel engine boats in
an effort to reduce pollution in the lake.
</P>
<P>
In a related move, nine counties near the lake have closed down
1,600 small paper mills, leather processing and dying factories,
and oil refineries, and nearby Renqiu City has closed 26 small
factories.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the amount of industrial waste water discharged into
the lake has been greatly reduced after the closing of those small
factories.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Enter World Telecoms Projects: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian business people can
now enter world Telecoms projects but foreign firms are still
limited to a 35 percent stake in the country's projects, a
government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
L. Parapak, secretary general from the Ministry of Tourism,
Post and Telecommunications said that Indonesian business people
are now able to participate in overseas telecommunication
projects, particularly in Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia was one of the 68 nations involved in the World Trade
Organization (WTO) talks in Geneva on February 15 on opening up
world telecommunications markets.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia, as a developing country, has insisted on the stance
that basic telecommunications business in Indonesia is open based
on three schemes, the joint operation plans, management contracts
and joint ventures, in which a foreign investor is allowed to buy
or to have a maximum 35 percent share," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the limit was essential because there was a big
difference between developed nations' and developing nations'
telecommunications industries.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, as part of the deregulation program to
attract overseas investors, Indonesia will allow foreign investors
to set up wholly-owned businesses in the country.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are seven cellular operators in Indonesia,
three of which are partly foreign owned firms.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia will not open long distance telecommunications
services and international call services to foreign firms until
2006, he added.
</P>
<P>
The global telecommunications pact will take effect on January
1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The WTO estimates the world telecommunications market is worth
more than 600 billion U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Parapak said telecommunication investment in Indonesia would be
worth 15 billion dollars between 1997 and 2000, while the value of
telecommunications service might reach 4.16 billion dollars a
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
