<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Using Rare Earth For Farm Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, February 18 (Xinhua) -- China's Heilongjiang province
has successfully used rare earth for large-scale wheat, soybean,
and beet growing, with per hectare output increasing 10 percent on
average.
</P>
<P>
The province has added one billion kilograms of grain to its
harvest by using the rare earth compound in recent years, an
increase valued at 100 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Rare earth, the so-called "industrial gourmet powder," is a
kind mixure of trace elements. One U.S. expert calls the
breakthrough in applying rare earth to farm production the most
important development since the discovery of the rare earth
element over 200 years ago.
</P>
<P>
China is the world's top rare earth producer. Agronomists in
Heilongjiang, Jiangsu, and Hubei provinces discovered after years
of research that plants could have 10 percent higher yields when
rare earth was used in treating seeds or sprayed on plant
leaves. The quality of farm produce could also be improved,
agronomists say.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government decided to spread the use of rare earth
farming technology in the 1980s and built a number of rare earth
compound factories in Henan, Shanxi, and Heilongjiang provinces.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang has established a group to spread use of rare
earth compounds in crop growth and has held training classes to
demonstrate the technique.
</P>
<P>
Rare earth has been used for crops in many provinces and cities
by now.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
