<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renewed Clashes Reported in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government forces
and Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) guerrillas have continued
their sporadic clashes in the southern Mindanao island, making an
interim regional truce accord a scrap of paper.
</P>
<P>
Captain Noel Detoyato, spokesman of the Army's Sixth Infantry,
confirmed today that the latest of a series of skirmishes occurred
on Sunday night after some 100 MILF guerrillas attacked the 39th
infantry battalion at a village in Buldon town in Maguindanao
province.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, government troops fired several rounds of
mortar shells to repel the attackers. No casualties were reported
in the incidents.
</P>
<P>
The renewed clashes prompted the MILF to postpone its peace
talks with the government from February 16 to February 25. The
rebel group also warned to scrap the rescheduled peace talks if
the military continues its offensives against MILF strongholds.
</P>
<P>
In response, Detoyato said the clashes erupted only after MILF
rebels harassed the government forces stationed near the Kabulnan
irrigation project in Agwak town on February 14 and 15.
</P>
<P>
"It is (them) who are provoking us. We are just maintaining our
defensive positions," Detoyato said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Fortunato Abat, chief government negotiator in talks
with the MILF, also asked the MILF to refrain from conducting
patrols in the areas concerned to avoid further clashes.
</P>
<P>
On January 27, the MILF and the government signed a limited
ceasefire agreement to end a week-long armed conflict in Buldon
town which broke out on January 16 and killed 40 people.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway group of the Moro National Liberation
Front (MNLF), is now the largest Muslim rebel group still fighting
the government troops. The MNLF signed a peace deal with the
government last September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
