<HEADLINE> UN Finances Chinese Animal And Plant Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Researchers on animal and
plant species in Heizhugou, in southwest China's Sichuan Province,
has received 37,000 US dollars in funds from UNESCO to study
sustainable development and protection of the area's plant
resources and for ecology research.
</P>
<P>
Heizhugou covers an area of 180 sq km, and is rich in animal
and plant species, thanks to its complicated terrain and special
climatic conditions.
</P>
<P>
The region has 29 kinds of animals under state protection,
including giant pandas and snow leopards, and has 30 endangered
plant species. Its ranks first in Asia and third in the world in
number of species.
</P>
<P>
The Sichuan provincial government has also allocated 600,000
yuan (about 70,000 US dollars) for the research project. 
</P>
