<HEADLINE> First Overseas Bank Moves to Pudong for Yuan Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- CitiBank has become the first
overseas bank to move its Shanghai branch to the Pudong New Area,
to get involved in yuan-based business.
</P>
<P>
"The relocation is intended to make preparations to open a full
line of services in foreign currencies and RMB," according to the
bank's leading representative in China.
</P>
<P>
Central bank rules require all foreign banks to relocate in the
Pudong New Area before they deal in yuan. Pudong is a new economic
zone across the Huangpu River from the old part of the city.
</P>
<P>
After the relocation, overseas banks will be able to handle
yuan-based loans and accounts, provide guarantees and clearing
services, and deal in Chinese treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
They can keep a branch in Puxi, west Shanghai, or in the
downtown area, to provide foreign-currency services.
</P>
<P>
CitiBank has the biggest business network in China of American
banks, with branches in Beijing, Shanghai, and Shenzhen, and
representative offices in Guangzhou and Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
China has approved two groups of eight overseas banks to deal
in yuan on a trial basis. These include CitiBank, the Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd., the Industrial Bank of Japan, Hongkong and
Shanghai Banking Corporation, Daiichi Kangyo Bank, Sanwa Bank, and
Standard Chartered. Also included are International Bank of Paris
and Shanghai, a joint-venture between France's Banque Nationale de
Paris and the Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, China's
biggest commercial bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
