<HEADLINE> Infrastructure Growth In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- More infrastructure is being
built in the Chinese capital to improve its role as an
international city and as China's major tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the city built or improved ten roads, with a total of
76 kilometers, 14 flyovers, and 30 overhead walkways. The first
phase of the Badaling expressway, going to the Great Wall, was
completed, bringing the total length of the local expressways to
130 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The Central People's Broadcasting Tower and the eastern runway
of Capital International Airport were completed by the end of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Cultural facilities were also improved, including an expansion
of a memorial for the War of Resistance Against Japanese
Aggression, the Beijing Changan Theater, the Dongdan Gymnasium,
and the Modern Chinese Literature Museum, in line with the
capital's role as the country's cultural center.
</P>
<P>
The city also built more public facilities last year, including
a power plant connected to the Ming Tombs Reservoir, a
water-treatment plant, and a garbage processing plant.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that as natural gas from the northwest Shaanxi
Province is brought to Beijing the coming September, the added
energy supply will greatly improve the local environment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
