<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World No. 1 Deng Suffering from Waist Problem: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- China's table tennis queen
Deng Yaping, preparing for her title defense at the world
championships in April, was suffering from a waist problem, a
newspaper here reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I am worried whether I could maintain my technical form," Deng
was quoted by the China Sports Daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
The paper said doctors who examined the world number one last
week said she was suffering from protusion of intervertebral discs
in the waist area, which sometimes causes numbness in her legs.
</P>
<P>
Doctors said numbness caused by the illness is rare for table
tennis players but would deteriorate if not treated immediately.
</P>
<P>
She now has to wear a special belt around her waist to control
the situation, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Deng took the women's singles title at last world championships
in Tianjin, China, in 1995 and won the women's singles gold at the
Olympic Games at Atlanta last year.
</P>
<P>
Deng told the paper she has limited the training time to about
three hours a day but planned to increase in March.
</P>
<P>
"I always trained harder than the other players before major
events but this time my physical condition would not allow me to
do that," Deng said.
</P>
<P>
Deng, who was voted member of the Athletes' Committee of the
International Olympic Committee last week, said she would attend a
committee's meeting in Lausanne, Switzerland, on April 14-15 but
would bring a trainer with her to keep training.
</P>
<P>
The World Table Tennis Championships will open in Manchester,
Britain, on April 24 and conclude on May 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
