<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Than Twelve Million People In Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Beijing recorded 12.59 million
people who had lived in the city for at least half a year, in
1996, an increase of 0.7 percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
According to recent statistics, this figure includes 9.19
million urban dwellers and a rural population of 3.4 million. The
city had a registered permanent population of 10.77 million at the
end of last year, a rise of 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The local birth rate in 1996 was 8.2 per thousand, a rise of
one percentage point, while the mortality rate was 5.34 per
thousand, a rise of 2.2 percentage points, Beijing Economic Daily
reports.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the natural population growth was 2.68 per
thousand last year, 1.2 percentage points down from 1995,
indicating that, overall, population growth is under control in
the city.
</P>
<P>
Among those surveyed, 13.13 percent are above the age of
60. The city now has more than one million people at or above the
age of 60.
</P>
<P>
China, which has an official one-child policy, hopes to hold
its population to less than 1.3 billion by the turn of the
century, when 20.6 million more children will be born. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
