<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children of Parents With Ichthyosis More Likely To Have Leukemia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Scientists in central China's
Hubei province have found that the offsprings of people suffering
from ichthyosis, run a higher risk of having leukemia.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at the Pediatrics Institute of the No.1 Hospital of
Hubei Medical University discovered the connection with
ichthyosis, a congenital disease referred to as "fishskin disease"
that is characterized by rough, scaly skin, but which does not
harm the sufferer's health or life expectancy.
</P>
<P>
The research group was headed by Professor Zhong Weikun, who
began a survey of 46 children with leukemia and their relatives in
1991.
</P>
<P>
The incidence rate of leukemia among family members with
ichthyosis can be as high as six to fifteen per thousand, said
professor Zhong, while the general incidence rate of ichthyosis is
four per thousand and that of leukemia is five per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
Zhong said that it will be a major breakthrough for the
prevention and treatment of leukemia if the discovery can help
scientists find the genes that cause leukemia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
