<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Observers to See Both Solar Eclipse and Comet on March 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese astronomy scholars and
amateur star-gazers will have a golden opportunity to watch a
total solar eclipse and the Hale-Bopp comet at the same time on
the morning of March 9.
</P>
<P>
According to the Nanjing-based Purple Mountain Observatory
under the Chinese Academy of Sciences, viewers will be able to see
the eclipse in the northern-most part of Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, the northeastern tip of Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region,
and the northwestern part of Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The choice viewing site for the observation will be
Heilongjiang Province's city of Mohe, which is located at 52
degrees and 57 minutes north latitude and 122 degrees and 29
minutes east longitude.
</P>
<P>
The time to see the total eclipse in Mohe will be from 9:08 to
9:10 (Beijing time) on the morning of March 9.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the splendid long tail of the Hale-Bopp comet
will be seen to the southeast of Mohe with 67 degrees of elevation
angle.
</P>
<P>
The comet passes over the earth once every 2,500 years, and the
eclipse will be the last one seen in China in this century,
according to scholars.
</P>
<P>
The concurrent appearance of a total solar eclipse and a comet
provides a valuable opportunity for astronomy studies, and throngs
of astronomers, amateurs and journalists are expected to go to
Mohe in March.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
