<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Facing Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar government
was advised to declare a state of food emergency and appeal for
international assistance to ease food shortage caused by
prolonged drought.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar Agriculture Minister Brigadier-General Adam
Mwakanjuki was quoted by the official Daily News as saying today
that some people in several parts of Zanzibar and Pemba were
reported to be living on mangos in the worst-hit parts of both
Unguja and Pemba.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the recent wave of bush fires that has swept
several parts of Zanzibar is causing concerns among agronomists
and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
According to latest reports, more than 12,000 clove trees have
either been burnt to ashes or badly affected by the bush fires,
which are unprecedented in Zanzibar's recent history.
</P>
<P>
The bush fires increased as the sun has destroyed cassava and
banana plantations as well as fruit trees and coconut palms.
</P>
<P>
Rice fields in several parts of the Isles which had been
prepared for next month's long rains have also been ruined.
</P>
</TEXT>
