<HEADLINE> Central China Farmers Discover New Consumerism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in Xianzhou village,
in central China's Hunan Province, are spending more of their
income on books and magazines, which in turn are providing them
with benefits.
</P>
<P>
Having learned about new methods of cultivation, they built 51
steel sheds to cultivate vegetables last year, and with the
resulting per-ha income of 12,000 US dollars, their village has
become one of the richest in the Liuyang region.
</P>
<P>
This year farmers in the village have subscribed to more than
100 different newspapers and magazines on vegetable cultivation
techniques, and in rural parts of Changsha, subscriptions to
"Hunan Science and Technology News" are up 11 percent, and books
on practical planting, breeding, and agricultural product
processing techniques have become best-sellers.
</P>
<P>
According to one survey, newspaper and magazine subscriptions,
telephones, agricultural machinery, and insurance policies have
become four major areas of spending for farmers in Changsha's
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
As many as 21,000 telephone sets were installed in rural
households, and the number of mobile telephones and beepers were
up to 10,000 and 30,000 respectively in 1996. Per capita net
income of farmers has been increasing also, with last year seeing
an increase of 29 percent over the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
