<HEADLINE> Zambia Tightens Pollution Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is
tightening control over pollution while approving new development
projects, according to the Ministry of Environment and Natural
Resources here today.
</P>
<P>
To this effect, a new statutory instrument was signed on
Monday by Environment Minister William Harrington.
</P>
<P>
By such a move, the government intends to make it mandatory
for investors and developers to carry out environmental impact
assessment before putting up any structures.
</P>
<P>
Building or clearing on larger areas of land without
assessment or posing a danger to the environment will be stopped
with investors and developers punished, said Harrington.
</P>
<P>
He added that sustainable development demands that all
activities planned and designed should take environment into
consideration.
</P>
<P>
"Through this instrument, the Environmental Council of Zambia
will be further strengthened to ensure compliance. It is
therefore meant to make environment a prime consideration in all
areas of our socio-economic development," Harrington noted.
</P>
<P>
Environmental impact assessments will not only ensure that
developmental projects are environment-friendly but will also
ensure that the investors' long-term interest be sustainable.
</P>
</TEXT>
