One 4,000-square-meter supermarket in Jinyang in the Pudong
area offers numberous types of goods from food and clothing to TV
sets and appliances. It is one of two supermarkets opened in the
area by Nonggongshang Supermarkets, one of Shanghai's biggest
chains, which plans to open 10 more outlets in the suburbs this
year, said Yang Dexin, its general manager.
</P>
<P>
Yang explained that, with the rapid urbanization of the
outskirts, many locals have gone from farmland to factories and
businesses. Rural people, like their urban brethren, began to
develop a taste for supermarkets because of the wide variety of
goods and clean shopping area.
</P>
<P>
"This is a perfect chance for us to extend our business to the
suburbs," Yang noted.
</P>
<P>
Other major chains in the city, such as Lianhua and Yaohan,
have started to set up outlets in suburban Shanghai, and local
suppliers and cooperatives, a mainstay of China's rural commerce
and trade, are changing outlets in rural areas into supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that a supermarket network covering both urban and
rural Shanghai is providing an important new production and
marketing link between urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The supermarket business has been mushrooming in Shanghai in
the past couple of years, and there are now about 800 supermarkets
for the city's 13 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
