<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania to Implement New Economic Reform Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Romania is to speed up its
economic reforms this year with a series of measures including the
privatization of 3,600 state enterprises and the freeing of
prices, Prime Minister Victor Ciorbea announced today.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange market will be liberalized and all
limits on imports and exports will be cancelled, he said.
</P>
<P>
Prices are expected to go up on average by some 50-100
percent. The government is imposing maximum prices on electricity,
heating, transport, medicines and post and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Romania raised the prices of gasoline and diesel oil on
January 1.
</P>
<P>
Ciorbea leads the new government that won last November's
general election on the promise of more market-oriented reforms.
</P>
<P>
The previous government had been slow to implement reforms such
as closing bankrupt state-run industries and kept the country's
currency artificially high against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Small businesses, the agricultural sector, energy-intensive
industries and privatized enterprises will be the focus of the
reforms, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said 70 loss-making state-run enterprises
are to be reorganized and will have to cut their workforce by 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
Salaries of state workers are also to be raised by 130 percent
to offset the impact of rampant inflation. The minimum monthly
salary will be increased to 150,000 lev (about 21 U.S. dollars)
from 97,000 lev (about 14 dollars), Ciorbea said.
</P>
<P>
The average monthly salary is now equivalent to about 48
dollars a month.
</P>
<P>
He also promised to double unemployment benefit and raise child
benefit and pensions.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and the International Monetary Fund, are to
provide some 1 billion U.S. dollars to help the country
implement these measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
