<HEADLINE> Northeast China Province Successful In Reducing Hunting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Jilin Province in northeast
China has been successful in the past year in limiting hunting and
increasing people's awareness of the need for wild animal
protection.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government decided to limit hunting in the whole
province for five years in January 1996, and issued a warning that
any government employee who was found hunting would lose his job.
</P>
<P>
The province has closed down four bird markets and set more
than 1,000 wild birds free, and built more than 6,000 ecological
sites to protect 200 million forest frogs.
</P>
<P>
A televised meeting was held in January to strengthen the
province's prohibition moves, in which Yang Qingcai, the governor
of the province, emphasized the role of publicity in the drive,
and pointed out that the five-year prohibition should also be
regarded as an effort to improve people's general level of
civilization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
