<HEADLINE> Australian Firm to Develop Hydro Project in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 18 (Xinhua) -- An Australian company will
invest and develop a 750-megawatt hydroelectric project in
far-west Nepal with the aim of exporting the entire electricity to
India, according to local sources today.
</P>
<P>
Officials of Australia's Snowy Mountain engineering Corp. these
days are busy in talking with electricity authorities in northern
Indian states in order to reach agreements on power purchases from
the West Seti project, about 400 kilometers west of Kathmandu,
they said.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government has given initial license for promoting
and developing the West Seti project to the Australian company and
the construction of the over 1 billion US dollar project is
expected to begin after the company finalizes the agreements with
several northern Indian states.
</P>
<P>
According to the Australian company, the Indian side has
responded positively and some State Electricity Boards in northern
India have formally endorsed their intentions to buy power
generated by the West Seti.
</P>
<P>
An Indian research institute earlier estimated that India's
northern region will face an electric power deficit of at least
21,000 megawatts in the next 15 years.  
</P>
