<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Gates Makes Hit at Seattle Science Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEATTLE, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Bill Gates, Chairman of
Microsoft Corporation, told an audience of 2000 today of a massive
investment planned for research, and the coming of three
dimensional computer grapics.
</P>
<P>
Gates, speaking on personal computers, drew the largest
audience yet attracted to lectures, seminars and discussions at
the annual meetings of the American Association for Advancement of
Science (AAAS).
</P>
<P>
With his electric notebook showing video graphics on a huge
screen, Gates, one of the pioneers of software for personal
computers and co-founder of Microsoft company, described the
implications for everyone in a world connected by interactive
computer networks.
</P>
<P>
"Every job today involves information," he said, urging
everybody to use electric communications such as E-mail to get it
in the Information Age.
</P>
<P>
At the presentation, Gates displayed the gadgets in his
personal computer including his E-mail which he said received
hundreds of messages every day, and the latest developments of
software.
</P>
<P>
Gates, who astonished the business community by abruptly
reinventing his entire company around the Internet in 1996, told
the audience that virtually everything Microsoft did these days
was focused on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
In his updated book, The Road Ahead, Gates said there would be
"no turning back" despite the Internet's irritating
deficiencies. "We can't anticipate all of the technical
breakthroughs that lie ahead," He said. "but interactive
networking is here to stay, and it's just beginning."
</P>
<P>
Gates' goal, which is to make software easier and more
enjoyable for people to use, is central to the success of
Microsoft, founded in 1975 and now one of the world's leading
companies. It has more than 20,000 employees in 46 countries and
revenues of 8.6 billion U.S. dollars for the fiscal year ending
last June.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the current fiscal year, Microsoft planned to
invest two billion dollars on research and innovation. Microsoft
Research was working on making the computer interact on more human
terms through, for instance, speech recognition and understanding
the user's natural spoken language.
</P>
<P>
To create more communicative visual interfaces for tomorrow,
the group was also engaging in many aspects of three-dimensional
graphics, including techniques for rendering highly realistic
scenes at low cost and creating more natural and lifelike
animation, and new ways to capture and represent everyday objects
and outdoor scenes in the computer.
</P>
<P>
Computer, information science and technology were an important
topic at the AAAS meeting, due to close Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
