<HEADLINE> Mongolia Develops Uranium Mines With Foreign Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia is reportedly
cooperating with Russia, the United States and Canada in developing its
uranium resources to boost the country's foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
A Mongolian-Russian-American joint test production of uranium
with an annual production target of 400 tons of uranium is
underway in Bayankhairhan of the central Dundgovi Province.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia, Russia and the United States are also studying a
resumption of uranium production in the Mardai mine in the eastern
Dornod Province, which used to be mined by the former Soviet union
unilaterally in the 1980s under a secret Mongolian-Soviet pact.
</P>
<P>
Canada joined Mongolia and Russia in an experiment of mining
the Kharaat uranium mine in the eastern Dornogovi Province. With
the experiment results expected to come out this year, the mine
will be put into operation in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia has an estimated 1.4 million tons of uranium reserves,
about 23 times the annual consumption of uranium in all the
nuclear power stations in the world.
</P>
<P>
Uranium is the main material used in nuclear power stations,
which provide 17 percent of all the electric energy production in
the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
