<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Declares Desire to Join NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria's new government today
made clear that it is keen to join the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), according to a report of the state-run BTA
news agency.
</P>
<P>
"The caretaker cabinet decided to express the country's desire
for full membership in NATO," the report quoted Foreign Minister
Stoyan Stalev as saying.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time since 1989 that any Bulgarian government
has declared the country's desire to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria was the closest to Moscow of any Soviet bloc country
and even after the 1989 drastic changes in Eastern Europe was at
best ambivalent about joining the 16-member alliance.
</P>
<P>
Russia has repeatedly expressed its strong opposition to NATO's
plans for expanding into Eastern Europe since they were officially
announced in January 1994. The alliance wants to take in former
Warsaw Pact member states from central and eastern Europe, but
Russia regards that as a threat to its own security.
</P>
<P>
"With its decision, the government responded to the desire of
the prevailing majority of the Bulgarian citizens," Bulgaria's new
president, Petar Stoyanov, said in a national broadcast statement.
</P>
<P>
The BTA report said that the government had entrusted the
foreign and defense ministers to draft preparations to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
The move reflects a policy turn under Stoyanov, an ardent
supporter of his country's accession to NATO and the European
Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Restructure Customs Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will soon restructure
customs tariffs to meet the country's commitment to the ASEAN free
trade area.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Economic Ministers of Thailand has Monday
approved a request from the Finance Ministry to cut, maintain or
waive tariffs on 3,419 items on a "fast track" list applying this
year.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from the Thai Government House today,
tariffs on 1.064 items such as garments, leatherware, and wood-and
rattan-based furniture will be cut from 25 percent to 20 percent;
tariffs on 241 items including synthetic fibres will be cut from
20 percent to 15 percent; tariffs on 478 items such as synthetic
rubber, thread and glass containers will be cut from 15 percent to
10 percent; and tariffs on 605 items including chemicals and
pharmaceuticals will be cut from 10 percent to 5 percent.
</P>
