<HEADLINE> Thai Baht Keeps Sliding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Thai currency baht has
continued to depreciate against the surging US dollar in volatile
trading.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange market still doubts the baht's stability
and selling pressure persists.
</P>
<P>
The central bank set the mid-rate for the baht against the
appreciating US dollar at 25.99 baht on Monday, one satang up from
the last trading day last week.
</P>
<P>
Heavy purchasing of dollars pushed trading to its highest point
of the day at 26.12 baht before closing at 26.06 baht.
</P>
<P>
Interbank rate rose to 20-21 percent because of the central
bank's steps to counter speculation and commercial banks' moves to
set aside liquid asset reserves.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign hedge funds have temporarily closed their position
in the Thai market and are watching events, according to dealers.
</P>
<P>
There was no evidence of strong attacks on the baht on Monday
and orders from Singaporean traders were of normal volume, traders
said.
</P>
<P>
Fund managers are waiting until late this month when the
central bank announces key economic indicators for January.
</P>
</TEXT>
