<HEADLINE> Funding Spurns New Railways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese railway authorities
are predicting a new railroad construction boom, crediting a 4.14
billion US dollars in government investment this year, today's
"China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that, the funds, up from 3.9 billion US dollars
in 1996, will be spent to lay tracks on 1,269 kilometers of rail
lines, open 1,261 kilometers of new railways and 444 kilometres of
second line rails to traffic, and to build 1,750 kilometres of
electrified railways.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quotes Cai Qinghua, vice-minister of railways as
saying that priority will be given to key projects that are near
completion or are in urgent need of transportation.
</P>
<P>
These include the Nanning-Kunming, Beijing-Kowloon, Nanjiang
(Turpan-Kuerle), Xi'an-Ankang and Hangzhou-Zhuzhou lines as well
as auxiliary projects of the Datong-Qinghuangdao railway, said
Cai. Many of the railway projects are in western China.
</P>
<P>
Cai said 700 million US dollars will be spent on the
Nanning-Kunming Railway, an essential project to facilitate
development of the isolated southwest region.
</P>
<P>
Track-laying on the 900 kilometer electrified line running
through the remote provinces of Yunnan and Guizhou and the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region, will be complete before March 20. The
entire line will open to traffic in November, Cai said.
</P>
<P>
Some 310 million US dollars will be allocated to finish
construction on the Beijing-Kowloon railway, which opened last
year, the vice-minister said.
</P>
<P>
Train services on the transport artery will be sharply
increased when a new national transportation plan takes effect on
April 1, ministry sources said.
</P>
<P>
Auxiliary work on the line will be finished by the end of June
to welcome the return of Hong Kong to the motherland on July 1,
Cai said.
</P>
</TEXT>
