<HEADLINE> Thailand Initiates 7-point Scheme for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 18 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has
initiated a seven-point program to improve the country's tourism
industry in cooperation with the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The program is aimed at boosting the tourism industry's
declining growth rate and increasing foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, tourism destination development is top
priority, as many sites in the country have been spoiled by
pollution and weak management. Joint government and private
actions will be taken to protect tourist attractions and improve
their management.
</P>
<P>
Immigration services will also be streamlined and criminal
activities at the county's airports eliminated.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will be made to liberalize the airline industry and to
build more international airports in provinces to bring in more
foreign tourists.
</P>
<P>
Actions will be taken to improve shopping services and refunds
on value-added tax for tourists and to crack down on cheating in
jewelry sales.
</P>
<P>
More international conferences and exhibitions will be
promoted, as businessman spend about 50 percent more than the
ordinary tourists.
</P>
<P>
Domestic tourism will also be promoted to lower overseas
spending by Thai tourists.
</P>
<P>
More overseas advertising will be made to cope with heavy
competition.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that in 1996 Thailand's tourism industry
earned 200 billion baht (8 billion US dollars) from 7.25 million
foreign arrivals, compared with 191 billion baht (7.64 billion
dollars) from 6.95 million foreign arrivals in 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
