<HEADLINE> Japanese Company Fined for Price Fixing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The Japan-based Mitsubishi
Paper Mills Ltd. has been fined 630,000 U.S. dollars in Canada's
federal court for its part in a price-fixing conspiracy in fax
paper.
</P>
<P>
The company pleaded guilty to two charges under Canada's
Competition Act for fixing prices in thermal facsimile paper and
refusing to supply thermal facsimile paper to a Vancouver
distributor.
</P>
<P>
The Court also issued an order against the company prohibiting
further anti-competitive activity, the Competition Bureau
announced today.
</P>
<P>
The sentence has brought fines to a total of 2.55 million
dollars imposed on Canadian, American and Japanese companies
involved in the conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
The investigation into the conspiracy involving other players
in the industry is still going on, the bureau said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
