<HEADLINE> Poland Tougher in Cracking Down on Drug Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Poland's law enforcement
departments have taken tougher measures to combat rampant drug
trafficking across the country since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to local press reports here today, the Polish General
Police Office have strengthened cooperation with the Customs
Bureau, the National Defense Bureau and other departments in
fighting drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
With increased personnel and funds, the police office has set
up special anti-narcotics offices in police departments throughout
the country.
</P>
<P>
The special offices will hire informants, use bugs, check mail
packages and take all other necessary measures in its fight to cut
off international drug trafficking routes, according to the Polish
General Police Office.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Poland has become one of the major trafficking
routes for international drug rings. Traffickers smuggle drugs
into the country and then sell them to western European countries.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Poland arrested nearly 20,000 drug traffickers,
destroyed six drug laboratories and seized 81 kilograms of heroin
and cocaine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
