<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Isthmus Nations Maintain Coffee-Retention Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The Isthmus countries will
maintain their coffee-retention program which coffee growers have
been implementing during the past two years to sustain coffee bean
prices on world markets, representatives of coffee growers
confirmed here today.
</P>
<P>
Participants from Ecuador and the six Isthmus countries,
Guatemala, El Salvador, Nicaragua, Costa Rica, Panama and
Colombia, met today in Copan, Honduras to analyze market
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The price of coffee beans has been rising rapidly on the New
York Exchange in recent weeks and reached 180 U.S. dollars per
46-kilogram sack last weekend.
</P>
<P>
However, the Costa Rican Coffee Institute (ICAFE) has warned
against exaggerated optimism. Institute president Alonso Lara
affirmed today that "great caution" should be taken by
coffee-growing countries since international market quotations had
been characterized by huge price fluctuations in the past few
years.
</P>
<P>
After several days of a sustained rise, coffee bean prices
dropped slightly Friday in face of rumors that Brazil's harvest --
the largest in the world -- could be bigger than expected.
</P>
<P>
Coffee prices have risen precisely because of a drop in
production, especially in Colombia, the second biggest producer in
the world, and because of lower stock levels in the hands of
dealers.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica's 80,000 coffee growers are hoping to benefit from
the hike in coffee prices, but production this year will be
affected by last July's floods and several pest infestations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
