<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improved Bus Plan Emphasized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Beijing municipal government
is being urged to focus on improving urban public transport
facilities and stemming the sector's decline, "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Beijing Municipal People's Political
Consultative Conference (BMPPCC) have called for the adoption of a
comprehensive urban transportation development strategy for
different traffic forms, especially buses and subways.
</P>
<P>
At the on-going six-day fifth session of the eighth BMPPCC,
which opened last Saturday, members said that it is necessary to
give priority to developing the public transport sector under the
city's special circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Yang Dazhong, senior engineer with the Beijing Public Transport
Institute, believed that the priority will raise the efficiency of
the road-handling capacity, ease the pressure of investment in
building new roads and alleviate traffic jams and accidents.
</P>
<P>
Yang suggested the municipal government adopt regulations
stipulating that various vehicles should make way for buses on
downtown roads, and vehicles cannot hinder buses near bus stops at
main crowded crossing roads or on the streets.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the municipal government should also collect
public transport taxes form the city's enterprises and institutions
in proportion to the total wages of their employees.
</P>
<P>
The number of automobiles in Beijing is growing at a rate of
14.5 percent annually and roadways increased only at 3.6
percent a year over the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Among vehicles on the urban road network, 48 percent are
official or private cars which carry six per cent of the
passengers while five per cent are buses and trolley-busses which
carry 31 percent of the total passengers.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, the number of automobiles reached one
million, which exhausted the capital city's transportation
facilities.
</P>
<P>
Some members attributed the city's traffic jams to the poor
transport management system and the blind development of private
cars beyond the handling capacity of the road network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
