<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Markets Create Jobs For Laid-off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Twenty retail markets are
planned in Beijing this year to provide jobs for those laid off
from State-owned enterprises, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing based newspaper quotes Cao Jie, a Beijing Bureau of
Labour official as saying that, as business people in these
markets are exclusively laid-off workers from State-owned
enterprises, the markets are named "self-support" to show those
people will be able to stand on their own feet.
</P>
<P>
The first such market in Beijing was established last November
in Xicheng District.
</P>
<P>
Business people in the market enjoy preferential policies, Cao
said. Those policies include stall fees that are up to 70 percent
cheaper and reduced administrative fees levied by the municipal
administration for industry and commerce and other departments.
</P>
<P>
These markets will be located mainly in urban areas where there
are a large number of laid-off workers and there are few
commercial establishments, Cao noted.
</P>
<P>
In this way, more laid-off workers will find ways to support
themselves and people around these markets will get conveniences.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government will help laid-off workers to run
their own enterprises to create more job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
As China adopts modern corporate systems, many employees in
State-owned enterprises have become redundant. In addition, many
enterprises are having difficult, forcing many workers to be
poorly paid or out of work.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the number of laid-off workers in Beijing is expected
to hit 200,000. There also will be 51,000 unemployed people and
175,000 people who are new to the labour market. Therefore, about
400,000 people in Beijing will try to find jobs in 1997, the paper
says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
