<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Men Mother-Fixated: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The widely-held belief that
Italian men have a mother-fixation was officially confirmed today
in a survey published by the national statistics office, ISTAT.
</P>
<P>
Both before and after marriage Italian men retain extremely
close ties to their mother and when marriages break down a quarter
of husbands go home to mother, the ISTAT survey showed.
</P>
<P>
Seven out of ten unmarried men over 35 years old still live
with their parents and continue to do so until they die.
</P>
<P>
Among bachelors of all ages, 21 percent stay at home with their
mother and another 21 percent live within one kilometer from home,
ISTAT said.
</P>
<P>
Only a fifth assert their independence to the extent of moving
more than 50 kilometers away from the maternal home.
</P>
<P>
In the case of married couples who do not live with their
parents, 78 percent of husbands see their mothers at least once a
week and a third do so every day -- the figure rising to 39
percent in the south, where more than half of husbands speak to
their mothers on the telephone several times a week.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that the telephone was the only indicator in
which women appeared to maintain closer ties with their mothers
than men -- over half of daughters speaking to their mothers daily.
</P>
<P>
After divorce only 17 percent of wives go back home, compared
with 25 percent of husbands. And among the unmarried, only 15
percent of women continue to live at home, while the percentage
for men is 21, the survey shows. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Copper Production will Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The world production of
copper concentrate in the period of 1997-2000 is expected to grow
17 percent to 8.1 million tons, a report issued by the Chilean
Copper Commission said today.
</P>
<P>
Oceania's copper production was expected to increase by 24.8
percent and Asia's by 5.7 percent, but the European and African
outputs were expected to reduce by 7.5 and 2.5 percent
respectively, the report predicted.
</P>
<P>
It said that copper producers in the Americas, where nearly 70
percent of the world's copper comes from, would increase their
output from the current 4.94 million tons per year to 5.76 million
tons in the year of 2000, an implied growth of 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
Latin America, representing 67 percent of the regional
production, would remain the most important producer of copper
concentrates in the world, and Chile, which alone provided 2.33
million tons of the continental production, would consolidate its
leadership in the area, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Chile, with an annual production of 10 million tons of ore,
accounted for 25 percent of the world production, and was the
world's number one ore producer.
</P>
<P>
With the materialization of new projects and expansions of
mines in operation, Chile was expected to increase its annual
copper output to 3.07 million tons in 2000, meaning it would
provide 53 percent of American copper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
