<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Los Angeles Lakers will
lose forward Robert Horry for at least six weeks after an MRI exam
revealed a sprained left knee ligament, the team announced Monday
from Inglewood, California.
</P>
<P>
Horry, acquired in January from the Phoenix Suns, suffered a
knee injury after drawing a foul from Seattle forward Terry
Cummings in the fourth quarter the Lakers' loss Sunday.
</P>
<P>
An MRI exam Monday revealed an isolated sprain of the medial
collateral ligament, a team spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Horry, 26, is the second Lakers starter in a week to go down
for an extended period with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
All-Star centre Shaquille O'Neal will be out eight to 10 weeks
after suffering a hyperextended left knee, fractured bone and
partial tear of the lateral collateral ligament.
</P>
<P>
Horry, who helped the Houston Rockets to NBA titles in 1994 and
1995, had been struggling this season, averaging 7.6 points and
4.2 rebounds per game. 
