<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buried Rain May Save Arid Plains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- China will capture and store
more rainwater to raise more crops and animals in the northern
part of the country, according to a report in today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Lack of water to irrigate farm land has plagued the northern
plains of China, while valuable rainwater drains uselessly into
rivers or evaporates, China Daily said today.
</P>
<P>
Underground water reserves have been consumed. The average
annual rainfall in the area is 500-600 millimeters, only 20
percent of which can be stored in dams.
</P>
<P>
Li Lierong, the director of Department of Geological
Environment under the Ministry of Geology and Mineral Resources,
said the now-empty underground caverns that once held the area's
water reserves are huge.
</P>
<P>
Li said rainwater now lost can be stored in them. The emptied
aquifers beneath the plains can hold 100 billion cubic meters of
water, according to a survey conducted by the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Water now pumped out of dams to prevent overflows and flooding,
and which now drains off into rivers to the sea, could be pumped
into the enormous underground spaces, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Storing water underground has worked well abroad, Li noted, and
is also being tested in pilot projects in Beijing and Shandong and
Henan provinces.
</P>
<P>
In Yanzhou, Shandong Province, more than 100 million cubic
meters of water from nearby rivers was pumped into underground
storage spaces, or "underground dams," between 1983 and 1986, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The water was used to help irrigate 16,600 hectares of
farmland, it said.
</P>
<P>
Five million cubic meters of water from the Miyun Reservoir in
Beijing was pumped into underground caverns in 1995 for later use.
</P>
<P>
Li's department will select more pilot districts in the area in
the near future. Scheduled sites include plains crossed by Haihe
and Runhe rivers and others near Taihang Mountains and in Shandong
Province, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
Li also said the ministry is studying how to desalinate
water for irrigation.
</P>
<P>
A pilot desalination program in Shulu, Hebei Province, helped
irrigate 10,000 hectares, raising the grain yield by 26.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Li's department also has pilot desalination projects in
Jingxian County, Hebei Province, and Jinghai County in suburban
Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Because the desalination projects have made notable progress,
Li said another pilot projects will be introduced in Jiangsu,
Shandong, Henan and Anhui provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
