<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second-hand Merchandise Popular in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Buying second-hand goods is
becoming increasingly popular this year although expensive and
fashionable goods still sell well in Beijing's large department
stores, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
"I came here for shopping because second-hand goods in this
center are priced low and are of rather good quality," said Miao
Yuhe, a worker who will retire in three years.
</P>
<P>
Miao bought six used tables for 150 yuan in the newly opened
Likang Golden Bridge Used Goods Trade Center, two km north of
Asian Games Village.
</P>
<P>
Miao's viewpoint, shared by most consumers of second-hand
goods, explains why farmers in suburban areas account for a large
part of the consumers of used goods.
</P>
<P>
Yet, Chen Jiang, manager of the trade center, said their
customers in the past month were not limited just to farmers.
</P>
<P>
Urban consumers of used goods consist mainly of single people,
elderly people, low-income families and a large population of
migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Beijing Municipal Trust Co. indicate that
60 percent of the company's two-million-yuan sales of used goods
in the first six months of 1996 came from urban consumers.
</P>
<P>
Average sales of Beijing Used Goods Exchange Center in southern
Beijing and its 16 chain thrift shops reach 150,000 yuan (18,072
US dollars) every day.
</P>
<P>
Many people in Hebei Province living around Beijing have come a
long way to buy used goods in his center since it opened on
December 26.
</P>
<P>
The used goods business promotes the sales of new products and
production of new generations of products besides meeting
different consumption demands, said Song Genquan, manager of the
exchange center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
