<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian PM Vows Determination to Join First Euro Wave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi today reiterated the importance for his country to be one of
the first European Union (EU) members to adopt the planned
European single currency, Euro.
</P>
<P>
Prodi, who is on a second visit to Germany within ten days,
held separate talks with leaders of the German state of Bavaria
Edmund Stoiber in Munich and leading businessmen in Frankfurt,
mainly to convince them that Italy could not be left out of the
first Euro wave of states to adopt the single currency.
</P>
<P>
"Europe without Italy is not Europe," Prodi said, referring to
the cultural, economic and military importance of his country.
</P>
<P>
Italy is now the only stable country in the Mediterranean area,
the prime minister added.
</P>
<P>
The EU is targeting to launch the Euro by January 1, 1999. But
scepticism is growing over whether the deadline can be met as few
members have been able to fulfill the European Monetary Union
(EMU) criteria set by the Maastricht Treaty due to their sluggish
economy.
</P>
<P>
One of the criteria is that the budget deficit and national
debt of a member country must not exceed 3 and 60 percent
respectively of its gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Prodi indicated Saturday in Rome that Italy was already
reaching three of the five criteria. He also expressed confidence
that his country would fulfill all the five by 1998.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not coming to Germany to challenge the Maastricht
criteria, nor do I want to impose a different position on
somebody," Prodi was quoted by German media as saying in Munich.
</P>
<P>
The Prodi government, which has staked its reputation on
joining the single currency from its planned start-up, has been
jolted by earlier media reports that EU officials planned to delay
Italian EMU membership until the year of 2000 or 2001.
</P>
<P>
Some German bankers also indicated their rejection for an early
Italian membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
