<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Cooperates with U.S., Sweden in Elephant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is cooperating with the
United States and Sweden in the field of elephant conservation.
</P>
<P>
Official paper The New Light of Myanmar today quoted Minister
for Forestry Chit Swe as saying that in collaboration with the
Smithsonian Institute, the Metro Washington Park Zoo of the U.S.
and the International Foundation for Science of Sweden, a research
center would be set up in Myanmar that would be able to support
its efforts to implement a breeding program for captive elephants.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the 7th International
Seminar on Conservation of Asian Elephants here on Monday, Chit
Swe said that Myanmar has been cooperating extensively on
environmental and forestry issues both bilaterally and
multi-laterally, establishing strong ties with many renowned
international non-government organizations.
</P>
<P>
He added that Myanmar is committed to abide by the standards
and norms of the Rio Declaration and the Forest Principles since
his country signed the Biodiversity Conservation and Climate
Change Conservation at Rio in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The elephants of Myanmar range over a large expanse of the
country from the sub-temperate regions in the north to the
tropical rain forests in the south, playing a vital role in timber
extraction and contributing not only to the national economy but
also to the sustentation of natural environment. Myanmar has a
forest cover of about 50 per cent and most of it is natural.
</P>
<P>
The three-day seminar, co-sponsored by the Myanmar Ministry of
Forestry and the Asian Elephant Specialist Group (AESG), was
attended by experts from 12 countries including Germany,
Singapore, the Netherlands, Thailand, Vietnam, Malaysia, the
United Kingdom, the United States, Indonesia, India and
Switzerland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
