<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary, Romania To Form Joint Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Hungary and Romania, both
seeking NATO membership, agreed on Monday to set up a joint
peace-keeping force to strengthen their military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached by Hungarian Defense Minister Keleti
Gyorgy and his Romanian counterpart, Victor Babiuc, during talks
in the eastern Hungarian city of Debrecen.
</P>
<P>
The ministers told a press conference after their meeting that
the joint Hungarian-Romanian force would implement peace-keeping
missions of the United Nations, the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, the Western European Union and the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
They said the move was aimed at turning military ties between
Hungary and Romania into "a model" for the countries in their
region, and "a symbol of stability in central and eastern Europe."
</P>
<P>
Gyorgy and Babiuc also signed a inter-governmental secrecy
accord which would be conducive to expanding cooperation between
the two countries' armies and in military technology.
</P>
<P>
Hungary also has such accord with the United States, Israel and
Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Gyorgy and Babiuc also agreed to quartly meetings between their
countries' defense ministers, and monthly meetings between state
secretaries in charge of international affairs, to discuss
military cooperation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
