<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Public health care in China will reach the level of similar
systems in developed countries by 2010, the Central Committee of
the Communist Party of China and the State Council predicted
yesterday in a decision issued in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The comprehensive system will include health care services,
medical insurance, and the enforcement of public health laws. The
emphasis will be on preventive medicine, employing traditional
Chinese and Western medical practices.
</P>
<P>
-- Beijing introduced 2.26 billion U.S. dollars of foreign
investment in 1996, up 14.7 percent over previous year's same
period and a record number in Beijing's history.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Li Peng yesterday solicited opinions from
non-Communist Party senior officials about the draft report on
government work, which he will deliver at the upcoming annual
session of China's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
-- The troops and local residents of various ethnic groups in
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Regions helped each other and made
efforts for the goal of boostering economy and safeguarding
the country's border areas.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Railway authorities are predicting a new railroad
construction boom, crediting a 34.4 billion yuan, (4.14 billion
dollars) in government investment this year.
</P>
<P>
The funds, up from 32 billion yuan (3.9 billion dollars) in
1996, will be spend to lay tracks on 1,269 kilometers of rail
lines, open 1,261 kilometers of new railways and 444 kilometers
second line rails to traffic, and to build 1,750 kilometers of
electrified railways.
</P>
<P>
-- A master plan for Beijing 's economic growth was outlined
yesterday, covering everything from out-of-season vegetables to
honesty in government.
</P>
<P>
High-tech industries are the focus of Beijing's economic growth
for the coming year, along with public services, agriculture and
construction of residential buildings, said Jia Qinglin, Acting
Mayor of Beijing. 
</P>
