<HEADLINE> Ecuadoran Government Seeks Consensus on Resolving Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Ecuadorans may face higher taxes
as the new government tries to get to grips with the country's
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit of seven percent of gross national product
could be reduced by raising revenues, cutting government debt and
other forms of economic adjustment, Finance Minister Carlos
Davalos Rodas said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador has the lowest tax rate in Latin America and this
situation had to change, he said. The government also needed to
improve tax collection, especially from taxpayers who were able to
pay up.
</P>
<P>
He said the government was talking to other sectors of the
economy in a bid to reach consensus on how to resolve the economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The new government was formed after Fabian Alarcon was sworn in
as acting president on February 11.
</P>
<P>
He replaced President Abdala Bucaram, who was ousted by
Congress on the grounds of "mental incompetence" on February 7
following widespread protests against the austerity measures he
authorized to solve the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Alarcon, who will act as president until August 1998, has said
that his government will focus on stabilizing the economy,
reforming the political system and restoring the country's
international credibility.
</P>
<P>
The government was preparing a "large-scale reactivation" of
the economy to correct the budget deficit, to fight inflation,
unemployment, high interest rates and to reactivate the country's
productive capabilities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Alarcon's government has terminated Bucaram's unpopular
austerity measures including steep hikes in the cost of public
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
