<HEADLINE> U.N. Drug Meeting Opens Azerbaijian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Anti-drugs representatives from
30 countries and 15 international organizations gathered in Baku,
Azerbaijian, today for a U.N. meeting to strengthen drug fighting
in the Middle East, Central Asia and Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
Azerbaijian's President Geidar Aliyev told the opening session
that his country is becoming more attractive to drug traffickers
due to its geographical location and the loosening of borders in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
He said the country has had some success in combating the
production of drugs, but more preventive measures are needed to
stop traffickers.
</P>
<P>
Reports, from the meeting of the U.N. subcommission for
combating illegal drugs in the Near and Middle East, said that up
to 60 percent of the 30 tons of heroin seized and destroyed by law
enforcement agencies between 1994 and 1995 were caught in the
Middle East, Central Asia and Caucasus regions. 
</P>
