<HEADLINE> L. America's  External Debt Grows 3.4 Percent In 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Latin America's external
debt increased 3.4 percent in 1996 compared with its debt load
last year, said a report published today by the U.N. Economic
Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
The document points out that Latin America's external debt
climbed to 607 billion U.S. dollars in 1996 from 586 billion
dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said that last year's increase in the
region's external debt was the lowest since 1991 and that was
resulted mainly from the devaluation of European currencies and
Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar in the year. 
</P>
