<HEADLINE> Uruguayan President Travels to Antarctica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Uruguayan President Julio
Maria Sanguinetti left today for Antarctica to supervise the
activities that his country is carrying out on the General Artigas
Scientific Base.
</P>
<P>
The president will land at Punta Arenas, Chile, from where he
will depart by plane tomorrow to visit the Lt. Marsh Antarctic
Base.
</P>
<P>
Then Sanguinetti will be taken by helicopter to the Artigas
Base where he is scheduled to arrive at noon tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The president will visit the facilities and meet with the
officials and scientists who are working on the base.
</P>
<P>
He will inaugurate the satellite telephone system to start up
two telephone access lines and a third for data transmission. The
system will enable Uruguayans stationed on Antarctica to link up
with Uruguay at the cost of a local telephone call.
</P>
<P>
Among the 30 people who are accompanying Sanguinetti are Deputy
Foreign Minister Carlos Perez del Castillo and Deputy Defense
Minister Juan Luis Storace as well as Army Commander in Chief Raul
Mermot.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay's Artigas Antarctic Scientific Base, inaugurated on
December 10, 1984, is located on King George Island which forms
part of the South Shetland archipelago.
</P>
<P>
The Uruguayans who work on the base carry out research on life
sciences all year round -- and especially in the summer -- such as
those concerning the inhibiting factors of arteriosclerosis and
its relations with penguins, ocean, land and atmospherical studies.
</P>
<P>
Sanguinetti is scheduled to return to Uruguay on February 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
