<HEADLINE> Italian, Dutch Ministers Discuss Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Italian Minister of Environment
Edo Ronchi and his Dutch counterpart, Margaretha de Boer, met here
today to discuss environmental issues including a better motor
fuel.
</P>
<P>
They exchanged views on approving a European Union directive on
"auto oil", which aims at reducing such airborne pollutants as
benzene. They also discussed drafting a framework directive on the
quality of waters.
</P>
<P>
Ronchi said a Dutch proposal to "identify a quantifiable target
for reducing emissions of carbon dioxide," was a workable
proposition.
</P>
<P>
European Union environment ministers will meet on March 3-4 in
the Netherlands, which holds EU's presidency at present.
</P>
<P>
A proposal on lowering the emission of all gases which cause
the hothouse effect suggested two deadlines, a 10 percent
reduction in 2005 and another 15 percent by 2010.
</P>
<P>
To reach these goals, the two ministers agreed that national
and European policies and necessary measures, such as boosting
energy efficiency in industrial activities, and reducing the
consumption of fuels for transport, should be adopted. 
</P>
