<HEADLINE> Tajik Rebels Release All Remaining Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Tajik rebels headed by Bakhram
Sadirov today released all remaining six hostages, ending a
two-week crisis which saw 16 people taken captive by the group.
</P>
<P>
The six hostages, including U.N. military observers and refugee
workers and Tajik Security Minister Saidamir Zhukhurov, were freed
after Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov personally ventured into
the mountains to negotiate for their release.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader later apologized on Russian independent NTV
television for the hostage taking, but said he had no other option
to secure the return of 40 of his men from bases in neighboring
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The crisis started on February 4 when the rebels seized 16
hostages over two days, including Russian journalists,
U.N. workers and the Tajik security minister.
</P>
<P>
Sadirov had demanded that the government pick up and deliver 40
of his fighters from bases in Afghanistan. On Sunday, the
government handed over 33 men. Sadirov then released five of the
remaining 11 hostages in return for direct talks with the
president.
</P>
<P>
The last six hostages were then released Monday evening. They
were the Tajik security minister, U.N. military observers from
Switzerland and Ukraine, and U.N. refugee workers from Nigeria,
Russia and Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time the rebels have taken hostages. In
December, they took 23 people, including U.N. workers, who were
all released unharmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
