<HEADLINE> Philippine Schools to Teach Migration Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine public schools
nationwide will teach a course on international migration starting
in June to build a "globally conscious citizenry," a local
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The departments of education, labor and foreign affairs signed
an agreement Monday to formalize the use of education modules on
international migration and its significance on development,
according to the Business World.
</P>
<P>
The course will be integrated into the social science subjects
of elementary and high school students this coming school year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon was quoted as saying that
migration is now an important element to the progress of developed
and developing nations.
</P>
<P>
Citing a study by the Commission on Filipino Overseas, Siazon
said one of 10 Filipinos resides or works abroad. The country has
a population of nearly 70 million.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said the course is not aimed at promoting
"out-migration" but to equip the Filipinos from early life with
the basic means to handle "the deepening globalization of the
workplace." 
</P>
</TEXT>
