<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin America's External Debt on Rise in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Latin America's external
debt amounted to 607 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, or a 3.4
percent rise over the previous year's 586 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to a U.N. report, this is the lowest growth rate
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The report, released here today by the U.N. Economic Commission
for Latin America and the Caribbean (CEPAL), said that the lower
values of European currencies and Japanese yen versus the dollar
in 1996 contributed greatly to the low growth rate.
</P>
<P>
While Venezuela, Peru and Chile maintained their debt levels of
1995 of 36, 32 and 22 billion dollars respectively, Mexico was
able to reduce its external liabilities by 1.1 billion dollars to
160 billion dollars, thus saving an interest payment of some 100
million dollars, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Argentina, Brazil and Colombia recorded the biggest increase in
their foreign debts. Argentina's debt jumped to 96 billion dollars
due to government bonds and securities issued to finance its
fiscal deficit.
</P>
<P>
Increase in Brazil's private sector debts taken on to modernize
its industrial plants led to a 10 percent hike in the country's
total foreign debt. Brazil now is the biggest debtor in Latin
America, with 175 billion dollars of foreign liabilities.
</P>
<P>
Next to Brazil was Mexico with 160 billion dollars. The total
sum of the two countries' foreign debt reached 335 billion
dollars, accounting for 55 percent of the total debt of the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
