<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reforms Test System in Primary Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 18 (Xinhua) -- At least four Chinese
provinces and cities have abolished an old test system in primary
schools in a bid to ease students' pressure.
</P>
<P>
So far, schools in Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin and Liaoning
province have abandonded the 100-mark exam standard, a scoring
system ranging from zero to 100 (full mark).
</P>
<P>
The system has been criticized because it encourages parents
and teachers pay more attention to scores than to whether a
student is actually learning anything, today's "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the four cities and province have began to use four
grades of "excellent, good, pass or fail" to define students' exam
results.
</P>
<P>
Students may feel less pressure as such evaluations are more
flexible, the paper explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
