<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Tory Government Wins Vital Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 17 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John
Major beat off Labor's attempt tonight to oust its agriculture
minister and paved the way for a full-blooded no-confidence
motion.
</P>
<P>
It secured a 13-vote win in a crunch Commons vote after all
nine unionists abstained.
</P>
<P>
The censure motion against Douglas Hogg was defeated by 320 to
307. The result means the prime minister can still hope for now to
soldier on until his preferred general election date, May 1.
</P>
<P>
Even before the vote, Ulster Unionist MP Ken Maginnis told BBC,
"I think the opposition has got its timing wrong, it's got its
objectives wrong, and it has got its relationship with other
parties wrong, and that is not a good sign for the future."
</P>
<P>
Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown also accused Labor
leaders of having botched it by failing to consult other parties
before making the censure vote public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
