<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Condemns Israeli Settlement Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat today condemned the Israeli decision to build new
settlements and confiscate Palestinian land.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who made a brief stop here this evening before leaving
for Moscow, made the remarks at a press conference after meeting
with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak at the Presidential
headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
Accusing Israel of foot-dragging in implementing the Hebron deal
which was signed last month, Arafat said that the Israeli
violation concerning Jerusalem has been more frequent recently.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli decision to set up a new settlement in Abu Ghoneim
hill in east Jerusalem has sparked Palestinian outrage.
</P>
<P>
He said Israel has confiscated several thousands of square
kilometers of land from the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"Jerusalem is not only a Palestinian city, it is also an Arab,
Islamic and Christian one," he said, adding that another Arab
summit or Islamic summit is possible in case that Israeli
continues procrastination on peace negotiations on the city which
he wants to have as the capital of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Mubarak and Arafat covers the latest
developments of the Mideast peace process, particularly the
Palestinian-Israeli track following the implementation of the
Palestinian-Israeli protocol on Israeli withdrawal from the West
Bank town of Hebron, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the Hebron agreement signed last month, the Israelis and
Palestinians will begin talks on a final peace agreement within
two months. They will negotiate their final borders and the future
of Jerusalem and of the 144 Jewish settlements in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators will break into nine groups
from today to deal with pending issues in the Hebron protocol and
the interim agreement as a result of Sunday's peace talks between
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators, the first since the Hebron
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has said that the coming steps toward settling the
Palestinian issue depend on how the joint committees will work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
