<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Virginian House Approves Retirement of State Song </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Virginia's House
of Delegates today voted 100-0 to retire 57-year-old state song
"Carry Me Back to Old Virginia," which critics say glorifies
slavery, an Associated Press report said.
</P>
<P>
The song was written in 1875 by James A. Bland, a black
minstrel from Flushing, N.Y., and adopted by the General Assembly
as the official state song in 1940. It was written from the
viewpoint of a freed slave who loves Virginia. But the song was
with such words like "darkey."
</P>
<P>
In 1970, then-state Sen. L. Douglas Wilder, a grandson of
slaves who became the nation's first elected black governor, made
the first appeal attempt and "similar legislation became an annual
fixture, rejected every year by lawmakers who said the song was an
important part of Virginia's heritage," the report said.
</P>
<P>
But critics argued that the song was so offensive that it was
no longer taught to school-children and hasn't been performed at
an official state function in two decades.
</P>
<P>
A bill on the matter was approved by the state Senate on
January 28 and it now goes back to the Senate for action on a
House amendment that eliminated a provision calling for a special
commission to find a new state song.
</P>
<P>
However, some suggest keeping the song, but changing the
offending words, considering Bland was the nation's only black
composer of a state song. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
