<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican President Reiterates to Recede From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano reiterated here today the southern African country has
decided to suspend its membership of the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA).
</P>
<P>
Mozambique will withdraw from COMESA until the organization
makes clear its relationship with the Southern Africa Development
Community (SADC), Chissano said in a statement issued by the
Presidency.
</P>
<P>
Chissano will not attend the annual COMESA summit in Zambia in
April and his country will not approve the accord on the
establishment of COMESA, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Chissano met earlier today with three COMESA representatives
-- Kenyan Planning and Development Minister R.O. Oyondi, Zambian
Trade and Industry Minister Afeyo Manbayi and Malawian trade
and Industry Minister Chakakala Chaziya.
</P>
<P>
The three ministers were dispatched by COMESA Chairman and
Malawian President Bakill Muluzi to deliver a letter to Chissano
to invite him to attend the forthcoming COMESA summit.
</P>
<P>
Member states of the Preferential Trade Area for Eastern and
Southern Africa (PTA) signed in 1993 a treaty transforming the
PTA into the COMESA, which was to come into effect on being
ratified by 10 countries including Mozambique. enditem


