<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Reportedly Admits Spying for Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 17 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian named Emad
Abdel-Hamid Ismail, standing trial on charges of spying for
Israel, has admitted being recruited by the Israeli secret
service, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
MENA quoted General Prosecutor Ragaa el-Araby as saying that
Ismail, 24, has confessed that he met Azam Meteb Azam, an Israeli
of Arab origin, when he was sent by his company to Israel
for training at a women's wear factory.
</P>
<P>
Azam, who was working as a maintenance technician in the
factory, is also facing trial on charges of espionage.
</P>
<P>
Standing trial today at the Emergency Supreme State Security
Court, Ismail said Azam introduced him to two Israeli women, Mona
Shawahna and Zohra Youssef.
</P>
<P>
Later, when one of the Israeli women asked him to work for the
Israeli intelligence for 1,000 U.S. dollars per month, he agreed.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutor said the two Israeli women will be tried in
absentia for recruiting the Egyptian. No date for the trial has
yet been set.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to make peace with Israel but
ties have been cool. Israel has said Azam is innocent.
</P>
<P>
Azam and Ismail, arrested last November, could face up to
death penalty if convicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
