<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cameroun's Government Vows to Support Insurance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Camerounian Prime Minister
Peter Mafany Musonge said today that insurance companies can
count on the government of Cameroun for assistance and support.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed the government's determination to ensure the
adoption of new insurance rules in line with the Yaounde Treaty
when opening the 21th general assembly meeting of the Federation
of African National Insurance Companies (FANAF).
</P>
<P>
The Camerounian government will review the tax system
governing insurance companies and pay its debts to insurance
companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government will protect the state-owned insurance firms
when making efforts to liberalize the national economy, he
claimed.
</P>
<P>
The insurance sector in the country has improved considerably
after experiencing some difficulties in 1993 due to general
recession and its restructuring is now on course and has yielded
some positive results, he said.
</P>
<P>
He called for more professionalism and solidarity among
African insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
About 300 experts from 20 African and European countries are
attending the FANAF meeting which will end on Thursday. enditem

