<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Confirms Proposal on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has
confirmed that it has discussed with British officials the
British-back proposal to deploy a multinational force in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"The possibility of deploying a multinational force has been
discussed in depth twice with British Foreign Secretary Malcolm
Rifkind and Britain's representative for Cyprus, Sir David
Hannay," government spokesman Yiannakis cassoulides told
reporters here today.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said that at this stage, "we are not
aware of a comprehensive plan concerning this idea."
</P>
<P>
The proposal for a multinational force in Cyprus appeared in
Sunday's edition of the British paper The Sunday Times.
</P>
<P>
The paper said Britain would participate with a 600-troop
contingent in the 5,000-strong multinational peace-keeping force
to Cyprus under a plan to reunite the island.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the make-up of the force, Cassoulides said this
must be under a mandate from the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the Cypriot government "is ready to accept
participation of Greek and Turkish contingents in the force to
facilitate the decision to set up the force."
</P>
<P>
Cassoulides noted the commander of such a force should not
come from either the Greek or Turkish contingent but should
be a person from a third country.
</P>
<P>
He said as far as he knows the U.S. would favor Russian
participation in the force.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been partitioned since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
abortive coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community are intensifying their
efforts to try to reach a Cyprus settlement within the year of
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
