<DOCNO> XIE19970218.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberians Want African Peace-Keepers to Stay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Many Liberians wish the west
African peacekeepers stay longer in Liberia, a report reaching
here today said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope there will be request to allow ECOMOG (the
peacekeeping forces) to stay far longer than six months because
the new national army and police must be trained to become
neutural," said former Police Commissioner Brownie Samukai.
</P>
<P>
After a two-day meeting in Monrovia, the foreign ministers of
the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) decided on
Friday that the peace-keepers will start pulling out of the
west African country six months after the general elections
scheduled for May 30.
</P>
<P>
Announcing this at a new conference, Nigeria's Foreign Minister Tom
Ikimi said: "There will be a new armed force and a new police force to
carry out the duty of security and defence of the territorial
integrity of this country (Liberia)."
</P>
<P>
However, Liberians feel doubtful that their faction-ridden country
can produce a neutral army or police in six months and are pressing the
interim government to seek an extended mandate of the ECOMOG, which
has been in Liberia for seven years since 1990.
</P>
<P>
"I would love to see ECOMOG here another year after a successful
election," said university lecturer Jeff Jallah. "It will take time
for these new soldiers and policemen to understand their own role and
duties."
</P>
<P>
Former guerrilla leader, Charles Taylor, who started a civil
war in 1989, has also come out in support of a longer stay for ECOMOG,
a force he previously denounced as an occupation army, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
