<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Meets Albright on NATO, Franco-US Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 17 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today talked with visiting United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright on a series of international issues, notably
NATO reform and Franco-American relations.
</P>
<P>
Chirac told Albright that France did not "ask for" its return
to the NATO integrated military command structure, and that it
would consider this only if the reform of the military alliance
brought about "the emergence of a real European identity of
defense."
</P>
<P>
France has asked the United States to hand over NATO's
Naples-based South Command to a European officer, a request which
has been repeatedly rejected by Washington.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also said that whatever the result could be of France's
attempt to bring about NATO's Europeanization, France does not
regard the issue as a bilateral difference with the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would take a definitive position on the outcome
of negotiations with the United States over NATO reform before the
NATO Madrid summit in July.
</P>
<P>
France will most probably maintain its simple membership of
NATO while staying out of its integrated military command
structure if the United States refuses to hand over the South
Command.
</P>
<P>
Albright expressed her hope that her visit to France would mark
"a new page" in Franco-U.S. relations in reference to the tension
between Paris and Washington which mounted at the end of the term
of former U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher.
</P>
<P>
"This is a good start for the second administration (of U.S.
President Bill Clinton)," she said as quoted by French
presidential spokeswoman Catherine Colonna.
</P>
<P>
On NATO's eastward expansion, Chirac and Albright agreed that
it is "important to maintain stability in Europe."
</P>
<P>
They also agreed upon the need to reach an agreement with
Russia on relations between NATO and Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
