<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Draft Defence Policy for Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's national defence policy
for the forthcoming 21th century is expected to be drafted out
in May as a committee has been launched to take the job.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the 15-member committee here today, the chief of
defence staff, Major-General Abdulsalam Abubakar, said the new
defence policy should reflect Nigeria's posture home and abroad
in the next century.
</P>
<P>
He urged the committee, led by Air Vice-Marshal Al-Amin
Daggash from Nigerian Defence Academy, to evolve a vibrant and
self-reliant defence policy to meet the realization of
the nation's aspiration of a politically stable and united and
economically just country.
</P>
<P>
The committee, whose members come from the military, police,
security agencies and academics, is expected to submit its
report to the chief of defence staff by the first week of May
this year.
</P>
<P>
The dynamic foreign policy, fertile land mass, abundant human,
material and mineral resources of Nigeria have continued to make
the west African country a target of attack, envy, sabotage
and indirect military threat by some foreign powers, he said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria must not lose sight of various border encroachments
and other criminal activities by "some of the countries
contiguous to our nation", he said.
</P>
<P>
The general charged Cameroun of the so-called "expansionist
tendencies" on Nigeria's eastern flank, saying Nigeria must take
it into consideration when designing national defence policies.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Cameroun have clashed repeatedly since 1994 over
the ownership of the oil-rich Bakassi Peninsula. The dispute is
pending before the International Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
"More important to bear in mind is the current efforts by
superpowers to undermine Nigeria's influence in the sub-region," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The "negative tendencies must not be allowed to detract us and
jeopardize our efforts at achieving an enduring collective
security arrangement in our sub-region and Africa as an entity,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our national defence policy must be sensitive to
developments, whether external or internal, and it must retain
sufficient flexibility and a threshold below which a nation's
military preparedness must not fall irrespective of internal or
external changes," he stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
