<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Oil Reserves Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iraqi official said
today that the Iraqi oil reserves has been enhanced over the
past six years, according to the Iraqi News Agency (INA).
</P>
<P>
Fa'iz Abdullah Shahin, undersecretary of the Iraqi Oil Ministry
made the announcement in a preliminary study quote by the INA.
</P>
<P>
He said that oil exploration teams of the Oil Ministry have
been able to increase the state's oil reserves by exploring new
oil fields in the west of the country.
</P>
<P>
Shahin indicated that huge quantities of unexplored oil can be
added to the state's oil reserves which stands at 112 billion
barrels. But the official did not disclose the amount of the
newly-found reserves.
</P>
<P>
He said great progress has been made on negotiations between
his country and foreign oil companies to develop a number of Iraqi
oil wells and to increase oil production capacity to 6 million
barrels per day (bpd).
</P>
<P>
Iraq is seeking to increase its export capacity from 2.5
million bpd to 6 million bpd within six or seven years. Oil
companies from Russia, France and other countries have expressed
readiness to cooperate in this respect once the U.N.-imposed
sanctions are lifted.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has imposed sanctions on Iraq since 1991
after the end of the Gulf War to drive out the Iraqi troops from
Kuwait following its 1990 occupation of the oil-rich emirate.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been allowed by the U.N. to sell 2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil every six months to buy food and other
necessities to alleviate the sufferings of its people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's oil export shrank from 3.2 million bpd before the 1991
Gulf War to the current 2.5 million bpd because of the more than
six years' U.N.embargo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
