<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Welcomes Possible Israeli Withdrawal from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister
Farez Boueiz said here today that Lebanon welcomes an Israeli
withdrawal from south Lebanon, the Lebanese National News Agency
(LNNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Israeli proposal on deploying French
forces in south Lebanon after its withdrawal is aimed at
"prettifying the image" of Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu and "burning out the French role" in the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupied south Lebanon in the late 1970s and set up the
self-proclaimed "security zone" in 1985 to curb the cross-border
attacks by Lebanese Muslim guerrillas on northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
The 1,100-square-kilometer buffer zone has since then become
the last active battle front of the Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz returned home Sunday from a one-week visit to France,
where he had a meeting with his French counterpart Herve de
Charette.
</P>
<P>
Paris has held back its support for a so-called "Lebanon
first" proposal raised by Netanyahu to separate the Lebanese and
Syrian tracks of the Mideast peace process, and has categorically
denied an Israeli report that France agreed to send troops to
replace the Israeli forces to act as a buffer between Lebanon and
the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese foregin minister was quoted by the state-run
LNNA as saying that after the election of Netanyahu and
"negative impacts of the Israeli government's positions" on the
public opinion of the country and the world over, the Israeli
government thought it should do something to "beautify its image
and the image of Netanyahu."
</P>
<P>
Boueiz said that if Israel wants to withdraw, Lebanon will
welcome and "it is the obligation and duty of the
Lebanese state to prevail its authority, its forces and its
sovereignty on its land."
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. Security Council Resolution 425 is not negotiable
and there is no room for understanding or deals with Israel (on
the withdrawal)," the foreign minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
Resolution 425 calls for an unconditional withdrawal of
Israeli forces from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
There have been debates recently in the Israeli cabinet on
whether the Jewish state should pull out its troops from south
Lebanon after two Israeli army helicopters heading toward south
Lebanon crashed over northern Israel. Seventy-three soldiers and
airmen were killed in the tragedy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
