<HEADLINE> S.Africa-U.S. Bi-National Commission Meeting Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The one-day Third
Plenary Session of the South Africa-U.S. Bi-National Commission
ended in Cape Town today, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was mainly focused on reviewing progress made by
the commission's six sub-committees since the last session in
Washington last July, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The commission, co-chaired by Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and
his U.S. counterpart Al Gore, was established in 1995 and meets
every six months by turn in both countries.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference after the meeting, Mbeki and Gore
presented the united front despite their rows about South
Africa's proposed arms deal with Syria, a country the U.S. has
listed as a "state sponsor of terrorism".
</P>
<P>
They stressed that occasional disagreements on foreign
policies between the two countries would not damage their
mutually beneficial relationship.
</P>
<P>
The South Africa-Syria arms deal was left off the commission's
original agenda but was discussed in private talks between Mbeki
and Gore.
</P>
<P>
On this regard, Gore said certain issues were best discussed
in private and Mbeki said Gore would be consulted with before
South Africa makes a final decision on whether to go ahead with
the arms sale.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also discussed issues such as the Great Lakes
crisis and bilateral cooperation of law enforcement against the
drug and crime, a common threat to both the United States and
South Africa. enditem

