<HEADLINE> Spain, Egypt Sign Cooperation Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Spain today signed a
cooperation and coordination accord at the start of the four-day
visit of King Juan Carlos who arrived here tonight.
</P>
<P>
The accord between the industries federations of both
countries, was signed during the current visit of a 50-strong
Spanish businessmen delegation that is accompanying the Spanish
monarch.
</P>
<P>
It provides for promoting direct contacts between companies in
the two countries and the development of bilateral trade relations.
</P>
<P>
It also helps to identify those industrial projects in Egypt
which the Spanish side can help through offering the needed
technological expertise.
</P>
<P>
Juan Carlos and Queen Sophia paid their last visit to Egypt in
1977 when ex-president Anwar Sadat welcomed them.
</P>
<P>
President Hosni Mubarak met the Spanish monarch at the
international airport of Cairo and will have talks with him
Tuesday on the Mideast peace process, which was launched from
Madrid.
</P>
<P>
King Carlos opened the Madrid Peace Conference in 1991 which
brought the Arabs and the Israelis to the negotiating table and
set the land-for-peace formulas as the basis for regional peace.
</P>
<P>
The Euro-Mediterranean partnership process which also set off
from the Spanish city of Barcelona, will figure prominently on the
summit's agenda.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak-Carlos talks will also deal with bilateral relations
and joint cooperation in various fields especially economic,
investment and trade ties.
</P>
<P>
Carlos will attend a seminar on trade exchange, joint
investment and privatization in both countries to be held on the
fringe of the visit.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day visit, the two sides will also define the
timing of the meetings of the Egyptian-Spanish Joint Higher
Committee on the ministerial level to be held in Madrid this year.
</P>
<P>
He will also meet Egyptian businessmen over a luncheon and
speak on economic and trade cooperation between the two countries
and boosting joint projects.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade exchange between the two countries stands
only at 500 million dollars, with the trade balance tilting in
favor of Spain.
</P>
<P>
Spain invests over 85 million dollars in nine projects in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed an agreement on economic and industrial
cooperation in March 1991, an agreement on investment protection and
an agreement to avoid dual taxation in November 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
